text: Ok just to give everyone a heads up, there are two other monsters in this other than Big-G. One is a ground type, and the other is a flying type. These are two entirely new concepts not seen in the previous Showa(54-75),  Heisei(84-95), or Millennium (2000-2004) Toho films. However given the fact that the director, Gareth Edwards is a huge fan of the original films, I'm sure this brand new Godzilla will not be disappointing in any way to any G-Fan and will also hopefully bring in a new audience of fans to Godzilla. So yea the few glimpses of the flying monster in this trailer is NOT Rodan.

text: I think Godzilla '98's biggest problem wasn't that Godzilla was radically different. In fact, I thought Godzilla's design was better in that film than his usual, bulky, man-in-a-suit appearance. It was a nice change of pace, made the creature more modern and intimidating, yet still kept to the theme of giant nuclear reptiles destroying cities. She was defeated easily compared to the typical Godzilla, but only after she caused heavy destruction and nearly raised another brood of building-sized mutant lizards.  The problem with that film is that it wasn't very serious. Instead of focusing on the impact Godzilla has, we spend a lot of time with annoying characters and their first-world problems. This really wrecks the film's pacing and damages the tension in the action scenes, as it is difficult to care about what happens to the characters. But I'll still contend that Godzilla '98 doesn't deserve all the flak it gets.  This film, so far, seems like it will do a good job at keeping the tone serious, emphasizing that Godzilla is not only powerful, he's outright unbeatable. And nothing about the characters seems to be forced or slapsticky. My only problem thus far is that this trail uses the BWAAAAAH! sound effect. *eye rolls*  I'm really looking forward to it. Hopefully my expectations don't go to high!

text: He stands in fearful amazement as his hands slowly rises to his mouth, his jaw is agape.  Thunderous footsteps approach and his muscles are being commanded to move his body, particularly his legs--but they're being insubordinate. They won't follow the orders of his brain. Others are rushing by, in awe and delirious of the presence of the ghastly royalty among them now.   Alone on the street he stands and watches as the King of Kings, the God of Death marches forward laying claim to his new found kingdom. A kingdom he takes willingly with no politeness, with no courtesy.  For it was always his.  He is Godzilla. Hear him roar.

Have some faith, the effects supervisor for this film is the same man who handled the visuals for the Lord of the Rings trilogy, and those look brilliant even today, over ten years later.

text: I had about zero excitement inside me regarding this movie until seeing this trailer. I will admit, I was completely tricked into thinking Man of Steel would be good as well, so I might be falling into the another trap. But while that movie's trailers promised a great story and then delivered nothing but explosions and crap, this movie is hinting at exactly what Godzilla once was. A story of terror with the undercurrent of human involvement in both creating it and then attempting to stop it. Bryan Cranston immediately gets my interest up. Throw in Jesse Pinkman and I'll really be fired up lol. But seriously, Cranston adds credibility somewhat, and the trailer does a good job of showing not just how destructive this Godzilla will be, but how unstoppable he might be. That serves to pique my interest. I will give this movie a look. By the way, I grew up in the 70s and 80s as a bigtime Godzilla fan.

text: To anyone complaining about how he's not some "mutated lizard"; go watch the original 1954 film. While he was mutated by atomic testing, he was still an ancient, massive creature who was woken up and disturbed by the very same testing. The Heisei Godzilla was a mutated dinosaur...which is not in any way, shape or form a lizard.  The '98 abomination tried to make him into a mutated iguana. This was, among many other things, completely wrong.

text: Here's my theories right now.  1. What is GodZilla? Well its hard to tell, it's seem nuclear bombs didn't hurt the damn thing. Although it's still possible this creature is Scientific, if it's a creature that lived at the bottom of the ocean it's very possible the pressure would have made if stronger then nuclear bombs. However, this movie is deeply hinting it's a Kauji, which is cool to.  2. Will their be other monsters? Yes, but none from the original. My guess is after the nuclear bomb failed to work the Japanese scientist created a creature (or two if the rumors prove to be correct) to kill it. After they unleashed it the creature went crazy and only added to the problem, but because it's made to kill GodZilla that remains its prime objective. So I expect two monsters fighting towards the end of the movie, I also think the design of the monster will be a mix of past designs from the original movies. Actually rumors say that the creature will have to forms, an eight legged form, and a wing formed. Sound familiar? The name of the creature or creatures has been rumored to be MUTO's, this is all rumors though, their might not even be another monster.  That's all I've got for now

text: Some hypotheses that can be made from this trailer: 1: Godzilla's 1954 appearance is quasi-canon, and the creature was attacked with nukes, not the oxygen destroyer weapon. 2: Said nukes possibly temporarily knocked out Godzilla, but mutated him to possibly greater size and power by absorbing the radiation as he slumbered.  Alternately, the original 1954 Godzilla was killed somehow [hollow skeleton in trailer], but a 2nd creature mutated by the nuclear testing waited even longer to emerge, explaining the larger size than previous Godzilla.  Still nothing to indicate the look/nature of the Mutos, that's the biggest mystery.

text: Words cannot describe how excited I am for this movie, but this trailer has me a tad worried. Maybe its just me, but some of the CG scenes look…well…not good. Like when we see big G come rising from the ocean just before the nuke goes off. That water looks pretty freaking shallow for something like THAT to come busting out of it, and the water effects seemed off; like the ocean wasn't reacting as it would have had that actually happened. Also when we finally do see his face, Which was awesome don't get me wrong, it just seems to be lacking a certain…grit to it that real world things have. I mean look at the buildings to either side of him, then look at him. You can tell he's not really there, which I know he isn't but I was expecting it  to make me THINK he was. Anyway call me paranoid but those are my concerns. Still going to see it opening day though. May 16th can't come fast enough :)

text: I grew up playing outside from 6am to sunset.. you can ask Anthony Davis how early I'd get up to "play".. I'd play baseball, hockey, football, and play in the creek etc... Sure I loved video games and get obsessed with them like Street Fighter, Mortal Kombat and Sports games like Blades of Steel, Joe Montana then NCAA football, NHL, Madden etc.  However I was ALWAYS obsessed with GODZILLA!!!, my parents Mary Ryan and @[100005433220929:John Ryan's Pop] can vouch for this. I've seen every movie.. they always joke about how as a child I'd get so excited to watch Godzilla movies when they'd come on TV... The 1998 American movie version (with Matthew Broderick) that took place in NY was horrible, that wasn't Godzilla.. finally after over 10 years of waiting, Legendary pictures (who has made Batman etc.) Has appeared to make a worthy Godzilla movie with an apocalyptic/realistic theme with great actors such as Bryan Cranston (from Breaking Bad)... and my "inner nerd" & childhood is extremely excited to see a worthy movie title "GODZILLA" come to fruition this May.  Joellen Wesolowski jokes I'm more excited to see this than our wedding.. that's not true, but this is the 3rd (2nd is my bachelor party) most exciting thing I look forward to in 2014!

text: Holy Shit, this is awesome! As a huge Godzilla fan This brings me to tears. Of joy. Couple things to note though: 0:17 not the best place to put a nuclear power plant. 0:32 looks like Godzilla is heading to Vegas, 0:36 nice job making everyone think that Godzilla (or one of the Muto's) attacks New York with the Las Vegas Statue of Liberty, oh Gareth Edwards you cheeky bastard you, that's why I love you. 0:50 ded. 0:59 Oh boy there bringing 1954 into this, make things more interesting. 1:27 so apparently these Muto could actually be aliens, or ancient monsters awakened from a long slumber. Or just mutant monsters created by nuclear radiation like I expected. Plus it's not the best idea to have you eggs attached to a nuclear missile. 1:32 not Rodan, or Mothra people, new monster, wonder if that noise is it's roar. 1:45 seems like the flying Muto is having fun throwing those F-22 Raptors into the sea, also Monsters just love attack San Fransico and destroy national landmarks don't they? 2:01 either that's Godzilla or the another Muto (kinda has the same roar as the one at 1:32). 2:07 that's a nice looking leg/ arm. 2:10 How exactly are they out running that train? Plus Aaron's character would die either way cause if those Nukes are still active on the train they would go off during the crash, and Aaron would probably die from the fall too at 2:11, and it's obvious to tell that he's just running in front of a greenscreen at 2:07 but meh who cares. 2:13 there's the money shot. Love this trailer and cant wait to see this!!!! Please do not suck or I will hunt you down Gareth Edwards! Then finally *Insert Walter White reference here*.

text: I like how they are referring back to Godzilla's origins while still mixing/spicing thing up a bit with a tweak here and there. Besides the "glowing, bubbly" thing @ 1:27 in the trailer, there is another thing that caught my eye: the HUMONGOUS BONES @ 1:42!! This leads to a personal theory: In the trailer, it's said that the nuclear tests near the end of World War II were not just test, but an effort to defeat Godzilla, and it's entirely possible that the original Godzilla from that time era died, leaving only its decaying bones and its (only) offspring is the reason we haven't heard from it since. It could have grown in the time since then, and is only now appearing because its finally matured into a full adult, leading to an even CRAZIER theory that perhaps other "Nuclear" accidents and spills, such as Chernobyl and the incident in Japan in recent years were simply cover ups over time by the government to keep us from panicking over the truth that our inevitable end was near!!! O.k., I'm done :D

text: To be quite honest, I think a rebooting certain movies is a fantastic idea.  A lot of movies made in the 70's, 80's and 90's needs to be rebooted. Because some just suck horribly and the only reason people still cling on to them is because it is something from their childhood memories and they can't let it go.  I mean, I can think of a plethora of movies that could use a reboot.  For instance, The Matrix (1999) should be rebooted and I don't see why it can't be. The fucking movie is almost 15 years old now.  Hollywood needs to reinvent the thing with new cast and preferably Nolan/Snyder at the helm. I mean, just look at the action sequences in the recent Man of Steel movie. Picture that kind of chaos, but with Neo and Agent Smith.

text: Looking through all these comments, some people don't know anything about Godzilla. I really just see jokes about Breaking Bad (good show by the way) or people thinking this is a sequel to the shitty 1998 version, which it is not. Yes it is a reboot, but a reboot to a new series, just like the last 3 series. The original Shōwa series from 1954-1975, Heisei series from 1984-1995, and the Millennium series from 1999–2004. People go look up Godzilla on Wikipedia. You will see he has stared in 28 movies from 1954-2004 (the American 98 version doesn't count) as stated by TOHO that it is not Godzilla. He is also the only monster on the Hollywood Walk of Fame. He represents the arrogance of humans, a symbol of the atomic bomb and the destruction it caused Hiroshima and Nagasaki and it's aftermath during and after World War II, and a force of nature which can not be stopped by anyone or anything.

text: Clear your heads out because i see to many ill comments that are lashing at just a trailer. Yes they used the Space odyssey soundtrack. big whoop who cares unless you get butt hurt easily over nothing. Godzilla obviously wrecked Las Vegas (somehow). We will have to wait for the movie to find out if Godzilla is a Dino or something else. Other than the failed 1998 version, this Godzilla can without doubt be called America Godzilla and be the only USA Godzilla film. so either its a re boot or a entirely new version. Godzilla is much bigger than ever. For the non Godzilla fan boys out there the roar in the ending is not the entire roar. Godzilla's actual roar is hell long and ends off with a gargle noise like what you all heard in the trailer. Its not Rodan, Gigan, Mothra. Must be a new monster. There was a early trailer that came out last year which got taken down in less than a few days. In the trailer showed a dead Kaiju with a crap load of legs. if seen correctly there was actually two.

text: GODZILLA (2014): When Walter White (Bryan Cranston) wakes up from the series finale, he finds himself detained at a government facility. An official brings him up to speed on a situation that will very soon become a world-wide crisis: the meth he cooked has baked a monster- "Godzilla" - aka a lizard exposed to his formula in a desert raid of his lab. Feeding off of blue meth, Godzilla is in route to New York, where it intends to meet with the only dealer in the world still slinging White's Blue: Calvin "Koolaid" Kennedy (Craig Robinson). Now, in a race against time, Walter White must cook up a solution to save the world with the one person who may kill him before the giant lizard does: Jesse Pinkman (Aaron Paul). Rated R for strong language, drug use, violence, and destroying the legacy of one of the greatest shows on television.

text: Here's hoping the anti-global warming message is as subtle in the movie as it is in the trailer.  (Maybe I'm wrong, but "You're not fooling anyone when you say it was a natural disaster" and "it's going to send us back to the stone age" pretty clearly indicate this to me.  Also, Godzilla was apparently awakened in the 50s.  That's when America's frivolous consumer culture really took off. Yes, I know the original movie is from 1954, but including that reference was optional and I'm hypothesizing they had more than fan service in mind.)  Either way, this looks great.

text: Growing up during the 70's and 80's and "Creature Double Feature", I watched my fair share of monster movies. Witnessing a new Toho creature share the stage, like the three-headed dragon Ghidorah was always a cool factor for this movie genre. What can be accomplished through CGI is mind blowing, and it's exciting to see GODZ get a chance to be re-imagined with all this technology.  This new GODZ reboot looks tight and entertaining as long as the focus stays on the monsters,  and not another Niko & Audrey couple distressing about their failed relationship.  LOL

text: BLOODY HELL, THAT'S AMAZING. I know people still have their doubts about this especially after that evil film from 1998 (let's not go there) but from what I've seen, Gareth Edwards has done justice to the original and with this film, it's much like the original. It's not about the monster, it's about trying to get a message across like what Ishiro Honda and Tomoyuki Tanaka tried to convey across with their 1954 masterpiece in regards to the use of nuclear energy, meddle with dangerous technology and eventually you will lose control of it and it will destroy you. Personally, I think this film will do well and the fans will love it. As for not seeing his atomic breath, just wait, maybe Gareth Edwards has a surprise for us, if the effects of Godzilla crushing a city are this good then the scenes of Godzilla letting rip must be mind blowing.

text: On trailers like these, I like to look at the details and speculate  Main Trailer: 0:13 The airliner (Airbus A 380 or 340) appears that it made an emergency landing. Mechanical failure? EMP? Glancing blow? 0:25 Linear accelerator? Obviously some sort of underground science lab for physics.... 0:29 Same underground lab? Is it military, or is it civilian and the military is coming in? 0:36 Glancing blow by tail would be my guess, otherwise it would have been completely flattened. 0:40 prisoner? That glass partition, and he wants to "Talk to someone in charge". 0:44 If it is deep enough to pass under the carrier, it shouldn't be visible from the surface, especially if there is particulate matter and those search lights would create glare. Also, at that size, it should be crushed by it's own weight, especially on land. (Science SNAFU #1 and #2) 0:50 Thank goodness those destroyers were of to the sides of that dorsal spine. And that wave is going to cause problems.... 0:51 They're fucked 1:01 What is that fluid? That is radioactive waste that the USSR dumped, and it has a very nasty gash in it. Carried on land by Godzilla? Radiation doesn't cause mutations like this.... (Science SNAFU #3) 1:08 More than one creature, or just one? Judging from dialogue it can be guessed that they failed, yet we see the remains of one? 1:18 Shockwave is to slow, and sound comes on to early and shouldn't crescendo like that (Science Snafu #4) 1:25 Big gun? EM railgun? 1:28 Human weapon, or Godzilla eggs? Construction BY Godzilla? 1:29 Vessel or base? 1:31 Something big diving followed by the jets. thank you +Sandwichman1337 for pointing that out. I missed that on my first run through. 1:33 Three USMC assault carriers, so the jets are probably F-35Bs, soon to be used by the United States Marine Corps (Ooh-rah) 1:36 HALO jump. Spotters for artillery or do they have a  special weapon? 1:40 Civilian bunkers? 1:44 obviously they can be killed 1:47 Golden Gate. San Francisco. 1:50 The military jets were in flat spins, meaning stalls. I am guessing that they get a very nasty tailwind or glancing blows. EMP or mechanical failure are not likely because they should glide, and I saw an F-35 [probably a B model (I hope to get my hands on one of those) because of the lines on the back of the fuselage at 1:53] pilot punch out. 1:53 Canopy is still closed, so somebody didn't punch out.... Why? Pilot error or mechanical? Or is the pilot incapacitated (High G spins can knock you out)? 2:03 Signal flares. Danger close? 2:11 That Blackhawk has an engine fire and tail rotor failure (judging from direction of spin) 2:18 That classic roar and title....﻿  Teaser: 0:01 HALO jump means close-quarters action, so I expect that they have a weapon. 0:15 A whole platoon? 0:28 C-17 Globemaster III. Smoke flares to prevent collision with other jumpers. Also, for that cargo bay, it should be wider if it is a C-17. 0:47 Electrically charged smoke? I see a fair sized risk of the jumpers getting struck. 1:19 I still think that is a Linear accelerator. Obviously some sort of underground science lab for physics, either military or civilian. 1:20 What is the purpose of the train? Probably not armoured because it won't make a difference, but would probably set it down. And why a cargo train? 1:27 Obviously a military bunker 1:28 HAZMAT suit. Bio, chem, or nuclear weapon? 1:32 Crashing, or simply exploding on the tarmac? 1:34 What the fuck is that? nuclear torpedo? Suicide nuke for the ship to ram with? Some other weapon? 1:38 Underground or on a ship? Again, why HAZMAT? 1:40 Yeah, armor on the train won't help.... And that train is FUBAR.

text: Looks pretty good...  Also looks like Godzilla is even bigger than it/he/she was in Emmerich's 1998 version - which was the BEST GODZILLA MOVIE EVER, btw...  Other than an independently-made reptilian monster movie that for the life of me I CANNOT find online, in which the 'monster' is CGI (instead of an idiot in a gawddammed rubber suit - which is just soooooo scary - NOT) anyway, the monster was CGI & a monstrously fine beast, too - no walking around pushing over miniatures of Tokyo (or maybe it was Seol?), but an honest-to-gawd on-all-fours dinosaur-like meat-eating monster.  But other than Emmerich's 1998 "Godzilla" & that other reptilian/dinosaur monster movie I CANNOT find reference to, there are very few GOOD dinosaur/monster movies out there.  We used to watch those cheesy "Godzilla" movies when we were kids - the ones with Perry Mason in them - and LAUGH OUR HEADS OFF at those movies!  Did we ever think THOSE "Godzillas" were scary?  Hell, no!!

text: How it should have ended - Godzilla gets out of water, starts wandering about, gets a single bunker buster to the head and dies. The end. Or if some realism is added - Godzilla collapses under it's own weight and cooks it's own internal organs with the heat of it's own enormous body, shortly after suffocating due to not enough oxygen in our atmosphere to support such a huge body. Oh, no, wait, I'm thinking of the Pacific Rim, where monsters were teleported from another dimension... for some unclear reason. In this one Godzilla wouldn't be physically able to exist in the first place. I just don't understand, why all these films about huge monsters have to be so stupid and illogical. Put the physics aside - could they at least stop sending modern fighter planes into dogfights with giant sea monsters?

text: This move looks good! From what I've scene they've really done a good job with the design of Godzilla himself, keeping him true to original design while making a few improvements (in my opinion). From the response this movie trailer has been getting, I think this movie has a really good chance to be among the top blockbusters of the year, even rivaling movies such as Spider-Man and guardians of the galaxy. I understand that warner brothers and legendary don't want to push this movie too hard, but I think this trailer shows that people are excited and interested to see this! On a side note, There are plans to release a SH Monsterarts 2014 godzilla toy that will be released later this year, but with the size of this godzilla (from the looks of it larger than any other godzilla to date) will they remain true to their size scaling and make this one as big or even bigger than their biggest figures as of now(biolante/destroyah) or will they make it similar size to the a godzillas they've released already?

text: Wait wait wait. "In 1954 we awakened something" Coincidentally this is when the first Godzilla movie was released. Okay. Sounds good.  a few seconds later...  "There were nuclear tests in the Pacific." This is referring to Trinity (Fat Man, Little Boy, and a third code-name for a nuke that I do not recall). These tests were conducted on July 16, 1945. Let me repeat that. 1945 NOT 1954.  Now now wait a second. So they're saying they awakened Godzilla (1954) and the nuclear "test" (1945) were an attempt to kill it? Heck they even got the island in which the Manhattan Project (1942 to 1946) occurred. But really now. How is a test situated a whole DECADE BEFORE Godzilla's awakening have to do with the bombing projects?  According to the original movie... "Before being mutated by the nuclear fallout of atomic bomb tests performed on an island called Rongerik, which is close to Lagos Island, the island where Godzilla lived, Godzilla was a Godzillasaurus that had somehow survived the extinction of the dinosaurs in the late Cretaceous era."  Ugh totally ruined Godzilla for me as a true fan. At least GET THE LORE RIGHT.

text: All you need to know about the new Godzilla:  - Godzilla's Regenerator ability full-detail description: Godzilla has the ability to restore all of his body using radiation as long as a single cell nucleus remains intact and is able to absorb radiation. The skeleton seen in this trailer is the real Godzilla's bones from a previous body. The egg sac looking thing around the nuclear missile is actually a cluster of Godzilla cells laying dormant.  - Many Toho monsters are alive and real and make  appearances in this film: Zilla Junior (Godzilla: The Series), Clover (Cloverfield, Godzilla: The Series), Orga (Godzilla: 2000) all have been confirmed to make cameo appearances as well as be involved in the sequel.   -There are no jaegers in this film. All cross dimensional beings are considered non-canon.   - The flying monster is in fact Rodan.  -Plot: As the world begins to transitions into the thermo nuclear era, the Military discover Godzilla. They are scared of Godzilla so they try to use nuclear bombs to blow him up. Because of this Godzilla's body dies and he goes into a dormant state. The scientists begin to study Godzilla's cells and create the M.U.T.O.'s project to create a weapon even greater than the nuclear bomb through bio-engineering. They create a giant insect like M.U.T.O. and Rodan. They escape captivity and begin to wreak havoc upon the Earth. Godzilla is awakened but he still remembers how the humans attacked him and goes on a rampage. He eventually meets up with the insect M.U.T.O.S. and kills the insect one. Realizing how strong he is he decides to become earths protector for the glory of it all. An alienship with orga in it impressed with Godzillas skills in battle is revealed to have been watching the entire time. In the post credits scene: Orga releases an army of monsters including one semi sized monster (Clover) into the water near where the insect MUTOS was killed and begins to absorb its body.  Afterwards: Godzilla 1998- Godzilla : The Series occurs and somehow the government has managed to keep this entire truth a secrecy to the public. Then Cloverfield occurs and New York becomes monster island.  Second Movie Plot Speculation Destroy All monsters themed battles with Godzilla,Zilla, Rodan (who has been hiding this entire time), Clover, and Orga.and a Giant squid like muto who is clovers ally.

text: If Bryan Cranston is the man I think he is he won't settle for anything less than a powerful role in a deep, well thought metaphor :)  The "In 1954, we awakened something" is a reference is to castle bravo, the most powerful fission/fusion/fission device -- or if you prefer, disaster -- ever detonated by the united states. At 15 megaton it was literally 1,000 times more powerful than the bomb that leveled hiroshima.  The soviets responded with a 50 megaton bomb. The whole using nuclear weapons to defeat nuclear weapons is a fantastic allegory and makes this film seem like it might be a great philosophical suspense movie.  Movie night!

Could they have completely polished everything in the previews? Probably, but it would take longer and cost more to make them. Not to mention that most trailers are made by a different company than the studio making the movie.

text: People seemingly are confused about Godzilla. I'll explain it to you:  Godzilla is a force of nature. He represents the fears/terrors of the Nuclear Bomb--Hence the Atomic Age. He was created by such weapon of destruction,or you can say "awaken".   The film majority you guys know,"GODZILLA" that was released back in 1998 was NOT Godzilla. It's even confirmed to be Zilla. This was stated in GMK and Godzilla: Final Wars. Heck Godzilla even fought the creature,and killed it in seconds in the recent film.   Godzilla and "Zilla" are completely different Kaiju. Godzilla is literally a mutated Godzillasaurus. While on the other hand,Zilla is simply a mutated Marine Iguana.   As for people saying,"Godzilla can survive nukes"? Yes,obviously. Godzilla is capable of withstanding Black Holes and Falling Meteors at point blank range. He also survived in molten lava nearly 4 years,back in 1985. Godzilla only died TWICE. In the original film back in 1954,Dr. Serizawa created the Oxygen Destroyer,which evaporated the creature into bones. The second death was caused by a Nuclear Meltdown in his heart,which could literally destroyed the Earth itself.  Many people are confused,due to Zilla(1998 Film) being killed by Bullets/Missiles.    Godzilla, and plenty of other Toho creatures is capable of withstanding such weapons. As for Nuking,Godzilla literally absorbs the energy: He usually feeds on such power.

text: I am GOING to see this in IMAX. Why? 10 years ago, in 2004, after Godzilla: Final Wars was released, Toho announced Godzilla was going to retire for 10 years, until fresh blood was in Toho. In 2012, I learn that LP was in negotiations to make this movie. Then the first trailer hits. 9 years of waiting, and my blood was set aflame by that trailer. May 16th is 20 days after my birthday, 10 years after toho announced Godzilla's 10-year hiatus. I have waited a long time for this day, and I WILL see this movie in all its splendor. Hell, I might even invest in the 3D version.

text: "Nature has a way sometimes of reminding man of just how small he is. She occasionally throws up the terrible offspring of our pride and carelessness to remind us of how puny we really are in the face of a tornado, an earthquake or a Godzilla. The reckless ambitions of man are often dwarfed by their dangerous consequences. For now, Godzilla, that strangely innocent and tragic monster, has gone to earth. Whether he returns or not or is never again seen by human eyes, the things he has taught us remain."

text: For everybody who believe that 1:31 is Rodan, but you'r not sure like me, I have some rumors I read form an article that could make more sense to whatever was nose diving into the water. So there are 2 or 3 main Muto Monsters and from what most of us understand is that these monsters are insect like creatures that have multiple legs. Now according to rumors, There are 2 main monsters that are supposed to be based off of Mothra and Rodan. This definitely makes sense since we all saw the centipede or caterpillar like monster that was dead in the teaser trailer. This dead monster could be in fact be the Mothra like monster in its first form before turning into a flying monster. As for the Rodan monster. This monster could be a bird who's dna was mutated with reptilian dna. These rumors could be wrong but they do tie everything together and make the movie even more anticipating.

text: I have hope for this movie, not because who's starring, or special effects. But that one line of 'the arrogance of man...' and nature; Godzilla is a natural disaster made flesh. That's what Godzilla, at it's core, has always been about; not a bunch monsters fighting or the destruction of cities. Godzilla is a walking cataclysm that mankind is powerless to stop. You understand why mankind and it's armies can't defeat a storm or volcano, but watching them fail to bring down something so tangible really drives the point home.

text: I really hope this CURES my need for giant monsters destroying cities.  And no, Pacific Rim didn't do it for me. It was a movie that was quirky and annoying as hell with a ridiculous plot line straight out of the Power Rangers, and bad cast (with the exception of a few) who show absolutely NO character development throughout the movie.  The one thing that Pacific Rim contributed to was to Godzilla's popularity today. There will be a LOT of people seeing this film, due to the success of Pacific Rim, and we'll see Godzilla swimming in cash before we know it.  This movie, on the other hands, reminds me of Cloverfield much more, and I love it. Much more mystery, less of them showing the monster and it makes you wonder.  This, by far, is my most anticipated film of 2014, and I hope they deliver.
author: Crokita

text: This movie is so fucking predictable, here's what happens.. Heisenberg hatches the plan to cook up the purist batch of meth in order to sedate the monster. He and Aaron Taylor Johnson slowly push through the sphincter of the beast making their way towards the belly fighting off mutant tape worms along the way, it is at this moment Heisenberg leaps on the opportunity to use his catch phrase "i'm the one who's knocking". There (in the stink of it all) they meet and team up with Charlie Hunnam,, Don't ask... Soon after the meth is successfully in place, Godzilla feeling as if he just finished McDonald's #7 combo, stumbles about squashing the entire cast of that god awful show 'Jersey Shore'. Meanwhile an eruption of stomach acids forces our heroes to make the tough decision of exiting through the urethra, Charlie jumps with excitement. As they are making their way towards the shaft Aaron spots Elizabeth Olsen mounted on the back of a sperm (majestic as fuck) and immediately falls for her. After they make their gooey escape, knee deep in a watery pool of lizard shit, all seems well until later that month when Elizabeth misses her period... Following the credits is a potential sequel clip of Elizabeth birthing what one can only assume to be pop sensation Miley Cyrus.

text: Guys the more i research this movie the more worried i get, the director has stated heavily that the movie is mostly shot from the humans perspective and it looks like its going to be more based on the human sub-plots than Godzilla himself, he also said that most of the shots of Godzilla and the other Kaiju are shot from angles and in light settings where its going to be difficult to actually see whats going on. I don't know about anyone else but i would really love for this to adopt a more Pacific Rim approach and just show us Godzilla and the other monsters just beating the holy shit out of each-other in the middle of a city. This is being directed by the same guy who did that movie Monsters and anyone who's seen it would know that it was ridiculously centered on the human characters and featured barely any actual monster scenes and he said that he shot Godzilla very similarly to that. Please Godzilla don't be a fuck up I've been waiting for this movie for so long and I'm so worried that its gonna hide the action and try and be some human centered movie that tries to have a serious undertone to it, just give us what we want - Godzilla absolutely destroying city's and other monsters in clear scenes that don't try and hide the action to make us guess whats going on and for once in a giant monster movie just give us a clear fucking look at the monsters its one of the reasons pacific rim was so successful.

text: Nothing can beat Godzilla, the king of all monsters/kaiju. Nothing. Not even the so called "Jaegers". Godzilla ranks in the Category scale as "God" or "Infinite". Go Godzilla!  I'm definitely rooting for both the humans and Godzilla in this movie, because one thing that people don't know about Godzilla, is that he's neither good nor evil. He's just doing his thing, and it's in his nature. Just like the lions of africa and the tigers of asia.   I'm so happy that Godzilla is finally getting the right treatment unlike the 1998 disaster. I love the design of Godzilla too, it has that old and iconic look, but with a modern design reinforced by the CGI work. The iconic roar is also back! It sounds so damn good!   Now, all we have to do is wait and see Godzilla busting some Muto balls!

text: I would really like the film to be great, but there are a few things that have me quite worried.  No theme from Akira Ifukube~to not include the man who gave Godzilla his soul, is completely uncalled for. His theme is "The Theme" of Godzilla. Edwards says it will be in the "tone of Akira"  That just isn't good enough. The tone can be the new composer, but, the theme must be there.  It seems like he is going to have Godzilla killed, and there are rumors there might even be a second Godzilla, which I hope isn't true. I don't want to see the older Godzilla dying while the younger watch or vice versa. That might be the "secret" that these people are talking about regarding a plot line that improves the movie.  I have no complaints about the design. Its fantastic, the feet are a bit off, but nothing really that bothers me that much.  I have no complaints on the trailer or the teaser.  I just think that Godzilla has his theme like Star Wars must have its theme.

text: まとめ：予告編の使用曲 “レクイエム第２楽章 キリエ” について  【楽曲名】 原題表記：Requiem II Kyrie 日本語表記：レクイエム(安息を) 第2楽章 キリエ(主よ)  【作曲者】 Ligeti György (ジェルジュ・リゲティ, ハンガリーの作曲家, 1923-2006)   【詳細】 ●1965年発表。スタンリー・キューブリック監督作品『2001年宇宙の旅(1968)』で「モノリスのテーマ」として採用。『GODZILLA(2014)』の先行予告編(teaser trailer)および本予告編で再び採用。  ●『2001年宇宙の旅』において、モノリスは「神（創造主）の遣い」として描かれる。この「モノリスのテーマ」を「ゴジラ（予告編）のテーマ」として使用するということは、ゴジラをモノリスと同様「人類を裁く神の遣い＝GOD-zilla」として描くことを意味する。  ●ちなみに伊福部昭がゴジラで手がけた最後の楽曲も“レクイエム”である。平成vsシリーズの完結編 『ゴジラvsデストロイア(1995)』で、「ゴジラの死す」のテーマとして使用された。

text: I have two things to say: 1. To those who're saying "this movie is pro nukes", no it's not, okay, this movie is not supporting the use of nuclear weapons. If you'd do your homework, like many of us G-fans had, Godzilla is a symbol against nuclear holocaust, the character represents the pain, suffering, death and destruction a nuke can cause, and also how humanity is the real monster by creating these weapons of mass destruction. Godzilla is AGAINST nukes, not WITH them.  2. This movie is gonna kick that 1998 piece of shit out of existence once and for all. This is a real American made, and very realistic Godzilla movie, folks, not that Zilla '98 kiddy movie. P.S. When I say "realistic", I mean in terms of the scenario of how would people react if Godzilla was real, like the 1954 film. Not that '98 crap, which, BTW, is very UNrealistic and it's just an excuse people made up.

text: Why are these comments so full of ignorance?   Let me get this clear:  This is a reboot to the Godzilla Franchise/1954 Film. It's Godzilla's 60th Anniversary. This not a damn sequel to the Zilla' 1998. That wasn't Godzilla. That was an Entirely different Kaiju. Enough with the "Why are they rebooting Godzilla".   As for the idiotic Breaking Bad jokes. Enough of them! Yes, Bryan Cranston's Walter White character was phenomenal. But the series ended. He's a DIFFERENT character now. In a entirely different series to be exact.  To those that are saying, "Is that Gigan"? Or "Is that Mothra?" No. There will be NO TOHO Kaiju in this film, except Godzilla. The MUTO's which are the new monsters in this film.   Last but not least: Those that are saying, "Just nuke'em." Or " Jaegers can beat Godzilla." Please,get serious here. Godzilla is King of All Monsters for a reason! He fought mere robotic replica's of himself. Survived in Lava for years. Survived a Black Hole and Meteor POINT BLANK. What makes you think Jaegers can take him on?

text: From what I'm inferring, Godzilla isn't what the military has been "hiding" in all these trailers. They are hiding the M.U.T.O monster. The M.U.T.O is what caused the power plant melt down and the M.U.T.O is what the government/military is trying to hide. But it's out of control. When he says "Can we kill it?" he's referring to the M.U.T.O monster(s), NOT Godzilla.   My inference is that they awaken Godzilla on purpose to kill the monster(s). Godzilla is a good guy in the film.

text: Still not sure how it's going to turn out, though it seems to be better than TriStar Zilla at any rate. But until we actually see some extended scenes both of Godzilla and of the acting it's hard to judge since you can make ANYTHING look good if you splice it up enough into a short trailer. Still looking interesting so far.  One minor thing bugs me though, not a super big deal but I noticed it. The comment about the nuclear tests in the pacific being an attempt to try and kill Godzilla. That's like...the opposite end of where this all started. The original Godzilla was a symbol for the Japanese fear of nuclear weapons after WWII (ever watch the original? Ever notice that what he does and the peoples reaction to it is incredibly similar to the real life reactions to the nuclear bomb?). Again it's a minor thing and will be unlikely to make a difference in its quality, but seeing as Godzilla was always supposed to be an anti-nuclear statement it's odd that they choose nukes to fight him.

text: I admit I am late to speak about this but it has been much longer than normal to verbalize my thoughts and therefore put it in writing but now I feel like I finally have figured out what to say and how to say it and one word that I have had in mind… “Inevitable”. It is no secret that Hollywood is going in a nostalgic geek trend (while producing rather polarizing opinions) they are trying to dig up and look back at some of their great franchises. However, in all fairness I do not need to talk about that because this was inevitable even if we weren’t doing all these remakes and reboots because this franchise could not possibly die…. This title is so important that it would have happened eventually and to be honest I am genuinely shocked it didn’t happen sooner. It was in 2004 when the last movie made… 2004… 10 full years. I remember all throughout those 10 years of my youth thinking, asking, wondering, “Where is it”?Decades upon decades of being household name and then all of a sudden someone decides that it just stop existing?! Impossible! This was going to happen someday no matter what! But in those 10 years of waiting I had grown older, wiser, more understanding of the world and people and all my preferred fields of entertainment and in that time I had grown… Comfortable. My interests had shifted quite a bit and while I always thought and hoped I eventually stopped thinking about it. It was no longer a big priority and when I think about it I don't recall it had been one to begin with.... My point is that I moved on; in those 10 years this little franchise and the genre it inspired had fallen greatly on the scale of my many, many beloved genres and who can blame me? In those 10 years this genre got such little attention from the industry so I couldn’t help but give it little attention as well…. I guess in a way when Hollywood moved on from it so did I and I can’t really regret that because in those 10 years I developed such a high appreciation and understanding of fiction and feel all the more wiser and healthy for it…. Having said all that… While I had “moved on” I had never fully “forgotten”. There was always a voice somewhere deep in my subconscious that while far from loud, was never unnoticed. This voice was quiet, patient, and respectful but most of all it was curious. That voice always had one question that question was “when”….? Now… my friends… and relations… After 10 full long years of patiently waiting and patiently wondering… the day. Has. Come. My friends… That voice in my head as finally received its long-awaited reward. This is the year… This is the time… The day has finally come when the beast… the Monster… the GOD…. … THE LEGEND! Finally returns… BIGGER… STRONGER… AND READY!!! TO REMIND THE WORLD JUST WHAT IT WAS! IS! AND ALLLLLLLLLLLLLWAYYYYYSS WILLL BEEEEEEEEEEE!!!!!!!!! MY FRIENDS IT HAS! RETURNED! TO DESTROY! OOOONCCCCCCE AGAIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIN!!!!!!!! REEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEEJOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIICE!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! Okay I’m done goodbye

text: Saw the movie today.. it's been a long time since i have been SO dissapointed in a movie.. I thought this was going to be a more serious Godzilla, like a more Cloverfield-type movie, but this movie was just so cliché on every level that I checked my watch so many times i lost count. text: I saw the movie movie today! Ima give this movie a rating 7 out of 10. (Not going to spoil it so continue reading) Cuz they should of put more parts of Godzilla scenes. The movie is awesome, i gotta say that the movie is 5x better than the one from 1998. I promise you all will love Godzilla so dont worry. In this movie you might cry in some parts and there are some parts that are funny and there are some parts that will make you shocked and amazed. I recommend you seeing it with your boyfriend/girlfriend. There will be parts that cuts a scene unexpectedly. The movie will make you love godzilla more than the one from 1998. Keep in mind, this movie isnt the continuation (Not the sequel) of Godzilla 1998, its the continuation of Godzilla from 1954 and yes the movie is awesome. My opinion: this movie is AWESOME but not EPIC. I loved it and im looking foward for the 2nd movie! I hope you all enjoy the movie! It's worth watching it!

text: SPOILERS!!!        The company needs to get sued for false advertising I payed for Godzilla not the son of the guy that we thought was the main character. but seriously Godzilla is only in this for like 5 of the 120 minutes. otherwise it's focused on the very generic and forgettable "Bad guy" (or guys?). why did they cast Bryan Cranston or give him a wife (That isn't mentioned for the rest of the movie and doesn't affect the plot whatsoever) just to kill him off. also why even call it Godzilla? sorry I guess i'm just pissed off cause I fucking paid for this piece of shit that I waited years for! the ending is probably the worst part it is in no way satisfying and it gives you no closure that an ending should have. the movie has little to no story especially after Bryan Cranston dies, after that things just happen with no story (Also a funny thing I noticed is that kids have the magical ability to find there parents in seconds despite being in a crowded area where everyone is screaming and looking for there Children/Parents) and the fact that Godzilla didn't die at the end when it was totally built up for it sucked! (not that I wanted him dead but they totally made look like he had died) and then the credits just abruptly pop up without answering questions and totally building up for a sequel. however the fight at the end with Godzilla and the two things was pretty sweet (especially how he killed the second one) all in all i'd give it a 5/10 and that's being generous I am genuinely upset that it got a 8/10 almost everywhere.

They didn't show much of Godzilla (excluding the last 15 mins of the movie) and when they did the scene would change within seconds to something else. Real damn shame cause you'd expect to see more of the king of beasts yet the story is more focused towards people struggling & coming to terms with the path of destruction that follows it etc. On a scale to 10 I'd give it a 7 and thats being nice, the cast was awesome no denying, Godzilla? meh...each scene he was in felt like a trailer, meaning you're left wanting to see more but it never really happens. CGI was top notch though. Some will love the movie, others not so much...props for trying.

text: I watched the movie today, was super hyped about it. Came out super impressed and happy. This movie was just amazing. So many parts where I'm just breathless and had chills from sheer awesomeness (I'm not exaggerating). The part that got me was Godzilla's first roar, it was just EPIC. This whole movie is epic. Not to mention it stays pretty true to the japanese Gojira too (unlike the other Godzilla film) There is another big EPIC part of the movie for me, but I'd rather not spoil anything for you guys. I didn't expect it in the movie, so it caught me offguard and I was like "OOOHHHHHHHH" (which I'm pretty sure the whole theater had the same reaction). This movie is imo the best monster movie that I've seen that isn't Japanese (no offense, but you can't beat Japanese Gojira movies.). If you watched and liked Pacific Rim, then you will love this. I loved Pacific Rim, but this movie just blew it out of the waters. Definitely recommend this movie.

text: Ok I just watched the movie, and I know that nobody cares, but I'll just go ahead and say it anyway, because I need to get this off my chest. I'd like to say that I am not a movie critic, and I don't pretend to be, but this is just my opinion. I'll try not to put any spoilers.  I really wanted to like this movie...I really did, but it was just so... boring. Godzilla himself was only in the movie for like 10 minutes, I swear, time that shit if you don't believe me, the rest of the time the movie is just filled with people talking, so don't bother going to watch it in IMAX. It also didn't help that the whole story just felt so disjointed, halfway through the movie I just phased out and started looking around the movie theatre due to boredom. You don't feel for ANY of the characters (except maybe Joe Brody), and it was so frustrating how they cut away every time there was about to be a fight. Now I know that people say "Oh thats how it was in the original Godzilla movie, Gareth Edwards is just paying homage to that blah blah blah", but you're forgetting, this isn't the 1950s anymore, audiences have different expectations nowadays. Maybe old school godzilla fans will love this one, but I can say with some certainty that it won't win any new fans. To be honest I enjoyed the older Godzilla movies much much better (Godzilla vs Mothra, Godzilla: Final Wars etc). They may have been cheesy, but at least they had a much higher fun factor than this movie. The last time I was this disappointed in a movie was Man of Steel.  Well at least his atomic breath was fucking awesome....

text: Ich habe den Film Vorgestern (14.05) gesehen und er lag total unter den Erwartungen! Ich habe mit einem Remake des Original Godzillas von 1954 gerechnet, was eine Hommage an jeden Godzilla Fan gewesen wäre, und eben bei eine nette Idee zum 60 jährigen Jubiläum von Godzilla.  Aber nein, der Film musste typischer Mainstream-Trash mit tausenden Logikfehlern, null Spannung, idiotischen US Helden mit den sich der Anglo-Amerikanische Zuschauer besser identifizieren kann (Man befindet sich in einem japanischen Atomkraftwerk und von den führenden Wissenschaftlern ist nur ein einziger Japaner), kack schlechtem 3D (Abzocke) und null Mitgefühl für den eigentlichen Helden Gozilla, werden.  Und es ist noch nicht einmal spoliern wenn ich jetzt verrate, dass Bryan Cranston nicht der Hauptdarsteller des Filmes ist, sondern der Muskel-Idiot Aaron Johnson, den keiner sehen wollte und der noch nicht einmal ihm Trailer auftaucht! Denn Bryan Cranston stirbt in den ersten 15 Minuten des Filmes, ohne zu untertreiben! Wir Cranston Fans haben uns im Kino nur doof angeguckt und uns gefragt ob die uns jetzt verarschen wohlen!!!  Der Film ist eine Enttäuschung auf ganzer Line.
author: Heinrich von Preussen

text: I just came back from seeing it and it really was amazing! It's good to know that the disappointing Godzilla 1998 is behind us... And yes I know there are many worse movies than "G-98" but this was one that really hit the audience hard, sort of like Star Wars Episode 1 -TPM. ANYWAY, Godzilla 2014 is surely a BEAST of a movie. The movie really was emotionally immerse with it's fair share of hardcore and adrenaline pumped action sequences. Even though I partially agree with some critics about Godzilla not being the Star of his own movie, I'm glad the movie was about people, their lives and their struggles. It is after all meant for a human audience and not mini monsters right? Remember, when James Cameron said he altered the look of the Na'vi to be more human like in order for the audience to identify with the characters and story!

text: 5 Reason why I don't like Godzilla 2014 movie: 1. Godzilla is too slow, lazy, and weak. Why not just cut to the chase just have Godzilla at the city already instead of having military following it the rest of the movie. When Godzilla defeat male and female MUTO it went to sleep at night in destroyed city and then wake up in the morning. WTF! Seriously? Godzilla would never sleep in the city. Godzilla would just walk to the ocean and swim return to monster island (home) and then roar during sunset. 2. Godzilla atomic breath was too thin and short. I prefer the old classic big bang wide blue atomic breath. In the film, the atomic blue breath was weak. 3. Too much military action and less monster fight. Example: Godzilla was about to fight Male MUTO at Honolulu airport next thing you know you see them in the news. 4. Godzilla got his ass kicked more than it defeat male and female MUTO by tail whipped and atomic breath. MUTO is nothing compared to King Ghidorah, Gigan, Megalon, Orga, Destroyah, Spacegodzilla, Mechagodzilla 1/2/3, and Monster X Kaizer. 5. Too much Human motion less monster scene. What is this soap opera? This is Godzilla film not some dumb militarism movie. I watch many of Godzilla film I find show mostly about Godzilla fighting against monster and alien creatures than human motion.  PS: The only Godzilla version I like is Millennium Era Godzilla from the movie Godzilla 2000 to Godzilla Tokyo SOS.  I give the film an F as Failure.﻿

text: The movie was good, just wish they could have developed the human characters more. People complaining about how Godzilla's screentime being too short. Well, in my opinion they used him just about right. The teasing of the fight and then cutting it away was a smart strategy on the movie's part, it made everyone pumped for the final battle in the end. I mean, the reason it seemed like Godzilla was showed multiple times in the past was because the old movies were like half an hour to 1 hour long where in reality, the human characters were showed a lot more than he did. This is why people love the T-rex from JP, they didn't show it every five minutes, and when it did finally show up, people went nuts. This movie was 2 hours long, so if they showed him too much, people would have gotten sick of him, just like how people got sick of the Spinosaurus in JP3. They showed the MUTO's or whatever those things are, more times so that when the Big G finally shows up, people are pumped as hell for the fight. Same why people love the T-rex killing the raptors in the end of the JP film. Overall, it was a good movie, just wished they could worked with the human characters a lot more though

text: SYNOPSIS: In the beginning, a Japanese power plant is hit by an earthquake. The wife of the father is killed by radiation. Turns out, the dad cannot forget about the wife, so he keeps going back into the quarantine zone. He and the son (now mid 20s) both go back to look for the house, and discover it is radiation free. They find the power plant being rebuilt and reused by Japanese scientists. A huge flying insect that has the power to send electromagnetic pulses is at the plant, and it is set free. It continues on its way to eat nuclear radiation (that is what it feeds on). It goes on a rampage trying to kill everyone and find its mate to reproduce. Then, Godzilla comes in and beats the fuck out of them both and saves the world. The end.

text: Third viewing last night... a packed Mann's (TLC) Chinese Theater on a Friday night. Full of Hollyweird's finest, tourists from around the world and local film loving freaks n' geeks...  1.) The theater house booed when the Bay4ormer trailer finished, with a loud shout of "Godzilla & Pacific Rim all day every day!" from one movie goer...lol AWESOMETACULAR in theater moment!  2.) The audience applauded at every slow burn majestic reveal of The King Of Monsters, and as with my previous viewings, the third act was full of resounding cheers & applause at all the same beats, and when the final credits started to roll.  3.) My two friend's not familiar with Godzilla or any tokusatsu kaiju/mecha IP could not stop asking me (the film geek) questions about Ishiro Honda's 1954 original, and all kinds of fun "post movie high" theories about MUTO biology, the Big Fella's origins etc. Not to mention appreciation of the sound design, cinematography and kick-ass moments. They loved it.  ...good job Gareth Edwards, good job Thomas Tull. Ignore the negative comments most likely from millennial gen folk raised on Bayformers who wouldn't know a good/great film (let alone a summer entry) if it slapped them in the face.  This movie is a work of art. Made with thoughtful care of Ishiro Honda's 1954 original, and I'm sure Honda and Eiji Tsuburaya would love this triumphant return of Godzilla if they were still alive today. Wishing all the success to this film, and looking forward to more expansion of the daikaiju & mecha (Pacific Rim lover here) genre's film revival that Legendary has procured.﻿

text: SPOILERS* Movie was pretty good only right until the point Joe Brody (Bryan Cranston) dies. Then it just got stupid plot-wise. I mean, what a coincidence that his son (Main Character) of all the possibilities in life, would turn out to be the military bomb-expert who would save "Gojira" from the MUTOs.   Also, they keep saying that "Gojira" came to feed on the MUTOs, but it just fights them and it doesn't even consume them, leaving their corpses behind. And then it acts like it has a "consciousness". Isn't "Gojira" supposed to be an animal?  And that radioactive blue flame? How come it didn't kill anybody around it because of it's highly radioactive values?  TL;DR - Movie was nice, but it has too many Hollywood clichés. I could have sworn that I was seeing a Michael Bay movie.

text: If you are wavering on seeing Godzilla...  1) Ignore the negative comments most likely from millennial gen folk raised on Bayformers who wouldn't know a good/great film (let alone a summer entry) if it slapped them in the face. Third viewing last night... a packed Mann's (TLC) Chinese Theater on a Friday night. Full of Hollyweird's finest, tourists from around the world and local film loving freaks n' geeks...The theater house booed when the Bay4ormer trailer finished, with a loud shout of "Godzilla & Pacific Rim all day every day!" from one movie goer...lol in theater moment!  2) It's worth the price of admission via IMAX or the biggest screen possible in your area. The sound design, cinematography are fantastic - like seeing giant mural's of gargantuan forces on screen. All three viewings of mine had resounding applause & cheers for the big fella at all the same beats.  3) This movie is a work of art. Made with thoughtful care of Ishiro Honda's 1954 original, and I'm sure Honda and fellow tokusatsu film collaborator Eiji Tsuburaya would love this triumphant return of Godzilla to the silver screen if they were alive today to see it. I hope for more expansion of the daikaiju/mecha genre film revival that Gareth Edwards, Guillermo Del Toro and Thomas Tull/Legendary Pictures have procured these past two summers.

text: People are complaining that they don't show Godzilla enough, but isn't that what makes monster movies great? Now tell me what King Kong, Alien, Jaws, Cloverfield, and most recently Super 8, have in common? They all make you anticipate during the first half and then near the end they give you what you came for and show you the monster. That's what makes a monster movie classic. The anticipation of waiting for the monster and waiting for shit to hit the fan and when it does oh boy does it feel good. But i'll end my rant with with great quote by Alfred Hitchcock that applies to this so well "There is no terror in the bang, only in the anticipation of it".

author: toppsballer

text: Disappointed. Godzilla has less than five minutes of actual screen time (not counting close-up shots of his skin or Spines protruding out of the water), whilst the MUTOs shared a good 25% of the film.  [SPOILERS in review] It takes an hour and a half for Godzilla to actual start fighting and then they don't even show you the fight scene! They cut to black and the next thing you see of it is a destroyed city. Another fifteen minutes later we see the two MUTO converge on Godzilla and he barely even moves. He just keeps getting knocked into buildings trying to defend him self. There are two fight scenes between the two Kaiju, none of them last more than 2 minutes. Most of the film is pointless explosions - whether it be artillery, weapons, buildings or vehicles crashing. They tried to characterise the human's through lengthy conversations but they never put characterization on Godzilla himself. I was hoping it would be more like the 2005 King Kong where we got lengthy, intense (and most importantly memorable) fights and deep characterisation of Kong, often both at the same time but instead Godzilla was used more as a tool or plot point than a character which makes it hard for the film to be memorable in any way.  The only memorable events are Godzilla's roar at the end because it lasts so long (which is good, it's the only part in the film that gives a sense of awe). The chilling scene where his spines light up before he releases his atomic breath. And when the MUTO tap the ground and release EMPs (although this is only memorable because it happens every 20 minutes).
author: Zac Walton.

text: Godzilla (2014) 1/10 So there are several problems for me with this movie  1. The setup: If Nuclear Powerplants would work like that we'd all be dead by now. 2. Yes, humans can outrun superheated steam. 3. Safety zones? We need no stinking safety zones. (yes, still at the setup). 4. So your monsters like nuclear radiation? Cool. So why did they not eat that really juice nuclear aircraft carrier but instead chose to chomp down on a Russian nuclear sub? 5. Tsunamis don't work that way. 6. And while we're at it: No shop window / door is going to hold THAT amount of water back. 7. I know the US military must be completely incompetent, but you'd figure they could use a few MOABS or at least stop using peashooters to try and take on the monsters. And yes, a .50 cal qualifies as a pea shooter if you have a giant monster. 8. Really? You think it's a good idea to hold people on a bridge that crosses the narrow spot the monsters will go through? And for added "bonus" you put some tanks on that bridge? 9. I know Hollywood likes heroes, but nowhere would the "hero" have survived even 1/10th of what this guy survived without much more than a sprained ankle. 10. Way too little Godzilla and too many humans doing stupid shit.

text: Gonna see this tomorrow and form my own opinion because I'm seeing a equal amounts of hate and love in the comments.   The main complaint I'm seeing is that there isn't enough action or Godzilla.  Most of these seem to be coming from kids who have never seen any old Godzilla movies or goons who just wanna see constant action with no regard to pacing or tone. The old ones,  almost the whole thing is scientists talking about the monsters or some human subplot we don't really care for and most of the mid movie monster shots are just them swimming or walking towards the battleground for the end of the movie.  I think I'm gonna like it because it sounds like they tried to make a real Godzilla movie that long time fans will appreciate rather than Hollywood it up and pander to the brain dead masses like the 1998 version did.  Commendable they didn't go that route since all that matters now a days is opening weekend sales and with a big name like Godzilla they could have done anything and made the money they wanted  with no regard for killing the franchise,,,,again.

text: "The arrogance of man is thinking Nature is in our control, and not the other way around."  2014's Godzilla brings the King of the Monsters back to his dark and gritty roots. The 1954 film portrayed him as a destructive force of nature. He symbolized the devastation of the atomic bomb on Japan and its citizens. Here, Gareth Edwards depicts him differently. He's still destructive, but he's not the main threat; rather, he's an anti-hero fighting off the newly introduced MUTO monsters. This film's overall theme has to do more with how humanity has destroyed nature and thinks they're able to control and manipulate it. The MUTO are basically nature taking its revenge on mankind, and Godzilla is the force meant to restore balance (no Star Wars joke intended). Now, how well did they execute what they were trying to portray? Very. It starts slow, but it does a great job of building suspense and developing the human characters. I was highly engrossed in the film and exploring the characters, and I honestly shed a few tears during some of the more emotional moments in the film. They were that engaging to me. It all ends with the final showdown between Godzilla and the MUTO, with the humans trying to rectify the mistakes they made when trying to kill them off themselves. And boy, does the climax deliver in a big way. The visual effects were amazing and the cinematography was very well done. It was an incredibly satisfying way to end it. Overall, I loved the film and felt that it stayed true to the atmosphere of the 1954 original while still diverging from the formula and updating it to be more relevant to modern times (and quite successfully). There are a few flaws, like some obvious plot conveniences, but I was able to overlook them easily, so they're nothing more than nitpicks. This is also not a film to be viewed superficially. Many philosophical ideologies are brought up throughout the film to support the underlying theme, which is why Ken Watanabe's quote from the trailer that I used to begin my review is so significant. You must fully analyze this film to truly understand the message it is trying to get across. That is why I consider this film a near masterpiece.  tl;dr very deep and engaging if you come in with the right mindset 9.5/10

text: This movie was superbly done. The whole concept of the monsters arriving and wrecking havoc could have been idiotic, but the way that Godzilla and the M.U.T.O.S. are depicted and explained is very sensible. There actually isn't a bad guy here as the monsters are treated as animals, and, I for one, love that approach.  The M.U.T.O.S are very cool looking and original, and so is Godzilla. The CGI is amazing! This is probably one of the best looking blockbuster films that I have seen. My jaw of on the floor during the third act of the film, while has a huge pay off from the film's earlier teasing. Garth Edwards does an amazing job in the director's seat.  The characters and the dialogue are fine. Each actor does a remarkable job in their individual roles. They were believable, and the human aspect of the story never dragged for me.  Overall, Godzilla was very engaging, smart, and epic. This movie is not going to be a waste of your money. Hell, I want to see it a few more times.

text: I have yet to see this movie.   I've watched a lot of the Godzilla movies, 16 in total, (approximately).   And for me the best of those movies are when he he's not on screen all the time, it becomes repetitive.   The first of those films i ever watched was godzilla vs megalon, where he is only in the final act, and as a kid, i loved it! I really enjoyed the original as well, again, where he only really appears in the final half an hour or so.   That having been said, the movies where he is featured more prominently do work well for me, if the other monsters are featured long enough to, just to keep things interesting, i.e. godzilla vs mothra (1964), and godzilla vs destroyah.   Films like, godzilla vs biollante, and return of godzilla don't really work for me because he is on screen too much, and honestly, i get a bit bored!   i appreciate suspense films like cloverfield, jaws, and jurassic park, but that's just me.   so i'm interested in your opinions guys; are the critics over reacting about his screen time? Or does it really take away from the enjoyability of it, because for me i perception atm is that i will really enjoy it, but the reviews are making me sceptical. text: You know what? F*ck it:  This movie was badass. I don't care about what the critics say. I don't care what the nitpickers say. Yes, they hold off on the final battle, but to be fair, EVERY GODZILLA MOVIE DOES THIS. The final battle is always during the third act at the very end of the movie. Heck, even in the original, Godzilla only was in 17-20 minutes of screentime. The rest was all people. What's important is if the suspense pays off in the end, and by GOD does it pay off in this film. The ending battle here was the best monster clash I've ever seen, easily topping any Pacific Rim fight.  And what's wrong with the M.U.T.O.s? It's like you people don't even acknowledge they were there! Even though Godzilla wasn't in the first and second acts much, the M.U.T.O.s sure were! You got a ton of monster action throughout the entire film!  Also, the acting in this film wasn't THAT bad. I mean, jeez, you people are RELENTLESS. Sure, it wasn't Oscar-winning or anything, but it sure the f*ck was decent. Plus, it's hard to beat actors like Bryan Cranston and Juilette Binoche, who did such a fantastic job and set the bar really high for the rest of the cast early on.  Finally, you have to take into consideration that this is Gareth Edward's first big-production film. HIS FIRST HOLLYWOOD-FUNDED FILM. He took a monster that everyone previously looked at as silly, unrealistic, and cheesy and flipped the tide. Now people are wanting to see more of the big guy, more destruction, more monster action, more atomic breath (whether they say so through critique or not). I'd say that's DAMN impressive for a first!  I say bring on the sequels, Legendary. The movie had its flaws, but it would be tragic to see a series like Micheal Bay's Transformers get countless sequels and not see this film even get one. My recommendation? Ghidorah.

text: I mean, i'm a huge Godzilla fan. I've been a fan since i was like 3 or 4. But, i just didn't really like this new Godzilla too much. Don't get me wrong, its a fucking awesome movie and it sure was a HUGE improvement from the 1998 one. I know the reason why they held off seeing Godzilla REALLY fight to build suspense and all but i felt like they were just like teasing us with showing a few seconds and then cutting away, that happened a few times. And when they did fight it was like only a 30 minute part out of like a 2 hour movie. I really like how the japanese versions were where there was little camera time focusing on the humans and more action with Godzilla and the monsters. Thats what you expect with a Godzilla movie rather than an hour and thirty minutes focusing on the humans and their point of views. Then they leave little to no time to actually show Godzilla fighting the MUTO. Also they focused way to much on keeping things more realistic where in the other movies they would have portals to other dimensions and aliens from other planets and shit. I mean thats what you expect from a Godzilla/monster movie. We came here and paid good money to see Godzilla fight awesome deadly monsters for most of the movie, still with plot and some human parts. Instead we got point of views and experiences from people almost the whole entire fucking movie and little screen time to the actual reason to we cam to see the movie, to see Godzilla. To me, the plot is good, an awesome monster blockbuster like Jurassic Park or Jaws, and did kinda build up to the climax of the movie, just not what i expect from a Godzilla movie.

text: Well a sequel has been greenlit via Deadline Hollywood based off of the kick-ass performance of Gojira in both domestic and international markets this weekend (with Japan & China still to come). Do think it needs a sequel? Not really, I prefer one off movies where my imagination can roam because I think the film did a great job off the bat. Save the "insta-franchise" cash grab stuff for forgettable crap like Bayformers or Amazing Sony Man.  But this lover of the genre is more than happy the past two summers - Pacific Rim was the Saturday morning cartoon action/adventure take on the '70s to early '80s daikaiju/giant mecha/anime genres. While Godzilla 2014 was a modern update on the '50s, '60s, '70s era Saturday night drive-in sci-fi/disaster movies, featuring the most well known daikaiju of all time. Keep it up Legendary Pics, I loved them both immensely!

text: I just watched it today, the movie was phenomenal. There was so much suspense, and this sense of foreboding, and a feeling these monsters were really there. I loved the way the movie started out, the intro added up to the historical appeal of Godzilla, and the enigmatic story behind it all. I loved Bryan Cranston's acting, it was amazing the way he executed every scene, his emotions, his expressions, they were genuine and you could almost feel what he was feeling. Something I really didn't expect in the movie is that the battles didn't take place in a variety of places. I thought the monsters were going to roam around America destroying cities and towns, but their appearances only took place on a few cities, and places. I also didn't like the new profile they gave Godzilla, of almost this "Here he comes to the rescue", something cliché like that, from a Superman movie or something, "Here comes the world's new super soldier... An ancient giant lizard", that wasn't too bad, is just that it didn't give Godzilla the neutrality and indifference it has towards humanity, it made Godzilla look like the good guy, and he's nowhere near that. I also didn't like the multiple doses of human sentiment, and the fact that Aaron Johnson was another one of those "pretty-faced" protagonists, Hollywood has to quit this obsession with the looks, these pretty faces kinda distract you from whatever else is going on in the film. Even though the movie had its flaws, just like every movie of course, I think the movie was amazing overall. I loved the new monsters, I loved the acting, it wasn't that bad considering it was mainstream film, I think it was better than most I believe. The battle scenes were amazing, I don't have many words to describe because the battles were just intense. I loved the film, and I would love to watch it again. I really hope they make the sequels, although I'm hearing the movie is receiving a wave of bad criticism.

text: I saw the movie and was totally satisfied.  The one thing I was most concerned about was that the human aspect of the story would be nothing more than backdrop for the monster fights (as is the genre norm).  The actors turned in some excellent performances (they cast Bryan Cranston after all) and the action was incredible. The thing that really struck me about the movie was how it captured the essence of Godzilla's character.  Godzilla is such a great character because he is one of the great monsters of modern media.  A good monster embodies a value in its actions and appearance.  Godzilla is nature's retribution.  As the film states, he is a force of balance. That is what the 1998 version completely missed and what made that film a betrayal of everything the character was. Presenting Godzilla in a new way while remaining true to his character is what the film does best.

text: Guys, when people complain that there wasn't enough monster action and too many human scenes, it means that the human portions just weren't engaging enough to hold out for the monster scenes. And it's true: in this movie, they weren't. After Cranston's character was killed off, we had to endure a story dominated by uninteresting subplots for both monster and human (the MUTOs and Ford's family). Thus, this is why many think Godzilla's role felt downplayed in his own movie. Some Godzilla films got the balance right. See Godzilla 2000.

text: Loved this movie, although I'll agree that the human characters were underdeveloped. The whole point of Big-G is that he is indeed a God, uninterested and uncaring about the lives of the humans he is unwittingly saving in pursuing his personal vendetta against other big scaly gooey things from who knows where, but yet we put some faith in him, wonder if he's "good" or "bad". He's neither. Lot's of people complained that this movie isn't full of monsters fighting monsters, but I think it portrays the insignificance of humanity against nature perfectly, because we (the human characters in the movie and the audience) are not the centre of attention at all. We can only sit by and watch helplessly as the battle rages, getting glimpses of the creatures and coming to terms with their indifference towards us. They really couldn't care less if we watch them fight or not. They do their thing, swat us aside and disappear again, letting us pick up the pieces and wonder what the point of it all was. Nature doesn't have a point, it just has (in this case) freaking awesome lizard monsters with nuclear breath.  This is the thinking mans blockbuster, and is very much above the "destruction-porn" genre of recent years.

text: I am a huge Godzilla fan and have been for some time and I have to say... this movie was well worth the wait :D  Alot of people are saying "there wasn't enough Godzilla" in it, but I have to say that as a major Godzilla fan that really didn't bother me! Sure more Godzilla would have been welcomed but the suspense and the build up in this movie works extraordinarily well! This is what REAL monster movies are, not just mindless violence and monster mash-ups like Pacific Rim!  As for the MUTO'S I really thought I'd hate them, but I LOVED them! They were cleverly thought out foes for Godzilla and I don't want to put spoilers and ruin it for the people who have yet to see it, but some of the MUTO scenes were very frightening (if your looking at it through a "shit, imagine if this really happened or I was there" type of perspective, which by the way is the mind frame real monster movies are supposed to put you in)  This was an EPIC movie and when you finally get to see the monsters for the first time (especially Godzilla) it is absolutely mind blowing, and that is a priceless reaction you would NEVER get if you saw Godzilla within the first 20 minutes of the movie!  As for Bryan Cranston's early exit, yes it was sad and he played a fantastic part, but this movie was not made for Bryan Cranston, he simply played a part in a movie like ALL actors do! If you want to watch Bryan Cranston and Bryan Cranston only stick to Breaking Bad!! This is a completely different project which has nothing whatsoever to do with any of Bryan's previous work! Just because he showed an interest and decided to join this project does not mean he has to be in every second of the movie! Actors take different types of roles all the time small and big, its part of being an actor!  Sadly, due to all these flashy super hero/transformers movies people have lost what the true meaning of a cinematic masterpiece is, and if they don't see "action" every 20 seconds they get bored! They don't have the patience to actually follow a storyline and connect with the characters :( look at all the groundbreaking box office classics (Jaws, Jurassic Park, King Kong, Creature from the black lagoon to name a few) and the movies have PEOPLE and a STORY and is not based solely on the monster itself trying to" fuck shit up"! If this "bores" you might I suggest you carry on watching your little "super hero" movies or better still, GO AND PLAY A FRICKIN VIDEO GAME!  On another note, anyone excited for this "Gamera 2015" rumour?? :D
