text: Ok i will be the first to admit that Godzilla 2.0 as I would like to call it. Was far better then I was expecting.  It is a worthy tribute to the orgional and not the hack we got the last time. I liked it even better then Pacific Rim as at least this had a plot.   Which however does bring up a concern. Do you guys think there should be a sequel?  I mean where could they possibly go from here? Now while some might want to revisit the past.  I personally don't think that's a good idea.    What made this Godzilla work was that it was something completely new and unexpected.  It also succeed in setting up an interesting story.  One of which if anything should be expanded on.  I don't want Godzilla turning into another Transformers.   Which frankly has lost all direction.  The Island pitch I don't particularly like either as that plays to much like a Jurassic Park. Time will tell but let's just enjoy a very well made tribute to the king of all Monsters.

text: *SPOILERS* I've watched the movie, and in my perspective of things, I've always resented the fact that Brian's character was just tossed aside like a dried up orange before even half of the movie was done with. His 'son' and his story was just really bland and kind of a cliché. I've always hated clichés in movies that have  one character who's most of the time the main character and is like the ONLY person out of every other person to do whatever something big to like save lives of others and what not. Those tend to get really unoriginal fast over the years.  I'll be honest, I'm someone who loves good fight scenes in every movie I see and I was pretty annoyed that they kept cutting out Godzilla's scenes and got to those boring soldiers again each time. The whole plan of blowing up all 3 monsters at once with nukes was NEVER going to work from the beginning. The monsters feed off radiation and kept taking the nukes themselves, bring them on civilian lands and endangering millions. Plus, if they actually killed off Godzilla like that, just how they easily disposed the 1998 Godzilla, I'm sure it would've pissed off a lot of Godzilla fans in the globe. So that whole idea was just half-assed from the beginning.  The movie had some great moments and I've gotten a good laugh from one particular scene in this, so This movie wasn't a total disappointment for me at least. This Americanized Godzilla in my opinion beats that crap from the 1998 version in design and action play. That 1998 ver looked too much like a T-Rex in slanting position despite his size, couldn't even use the trademark Atomic Breath attack, and wasn't durable from human weapons. And now the 2014 version retains all of those traits that make him the genuine king of monsters we all know and love.  Overall, I say this movie wasn't the best of 2014, but it maybe worth watching for anyone who's still interested about see it. I would hope they could perhaps do a Mothra movie in the future.

text: Literally just saw the movie. They might as well have called it "Muto"!  Godzilla was the best thing about the movie, but was also an opportunity they kind of squandered. He ends up getting way too little screen time, and his fights were often obstructed by human action and TALKING. The humans were boring, and the lead actor had no charisma. The story didn't have the power behind it for them to have lingered on it for so long before getting to the kaiju. If you're going to linger over the story before the action, make sure you have a good, powerful, emotional, well-acted story with characters we grow to care about!!! It's weird, but the bus driver in the middle of the movie impressed me out of any of the other characters.

text: Hmm, I never realized this as a kid, but now at my age after re-watching some old Godzilla movies, I realize how much Japan hated Americans. Look at how Godzilla is depicted in the previous movies. Before he was a savior, he was an abomination with wide human-like eyes, which used to be what Japanese people looked at Americans as after World War II. If you watch Godzilla vs King Ghidora either English dubbed or Japanese, take a close look at the American soldiers. Pay close attention to the dialogue and how they act. Forgive me if anyone is offended by this comment, I'm just giving my analysis.

text: ---------SPOILER ALERT------------------  Everyone is allowed their own opinion and i thought id share mine  This was not my favorite, maybe i was just expecting too much from the awesome trailer. The human scenes were really boring, the acting was laughable. The buildup to then revealing the "Godzilla" name was too funny to take serious. The main character always ended up in the wrong place at the wrong time for some reason.  I also expected Godzilla to look a little more badass. He looked way too fat, which is weird to say for a creature. The only time he looked menacing was when he was coming out of the water. A lot of scenes did not make sense to me. The part i hated the most was at the end. Everyone surrounds Godzilla thinking that its ok?? No one knew if he was dead or not! No one knew he was on the humans side, for all we knew he was just killing the MUTO because of instinct. Was no one scared at all when he woke up? That to me was the nail in the coffin. I would seriously had rather watched the '98 version all over again, that Godzilla was pretty badass.  The part i did like though was the blue blast in the throat part, that was pretty awesome to see. Also the military scenes are always awesome to watch in these kinds of movies. Always hurts to see military die though, never want that to happen. But the planes and the action was great to see

text: I just saw Godzilla 2014 in IMAX 3D and I think everyone needs to stop complaining about the very limited screen time Godzilla actually had in the movie. Just like the original, Godzilla didn't get very much time on camera, which adds to the build up, suspense, and the awe when you finally see him. Just imagine the movie with Godzilla popping up and fighting every five minutes, you would lose interest and curiosity and it'll become another mindless monster mash movie. To backup my argument, some movies with it's antagonist on the screen for a small amount of time are: The Wicked Witch - The Wizard of OZ (12 minutes) Darth Vader - Star Wars: A New Hope (12 minutes) Hannibal Lector - Silence of the Lambs (16 minutes) The Joker - The Dark Knight (33 minutes) Which may seem long but is actually only 20% of the movie T-Rex - Jurassic Park (Not sure how much time but it is only a few minutes) Jaws - JAWS (Again not sure but it has to be only a couple minutes) The list goes on for many other lesser known movies. I loved the original, don't get me wrong. But when it comes to the actual production value of the two movies, Godzilla 2014 is much better. Better effects, acting, sound, and in some cases the music which can be opinionated but I think it was great. I would rate Godzilla 1954 9/10 because of the nostalgia and just the fact it is the original and paved the way for the new one. I would rate the 2014 Godzilla 10/10 because it was able to capture what the original had but make it even better. I already know a bunch of people are going to strongly disagree with me but you cannot deny this is the truth. In conclusion, please stop arguing that Godzilla didn't get enough screen time. 10/10 would watch again

text: I watched the movie yesterday in normal 2D viewing... To be honest I really wanted to love this film since I love the classic Godzilla movies but this 2nd attempt from america was pretty disappointing.  Doesn't help that the long start before we even get to see Godzilla in action wasn't a good start for the movie.  If they got rid of the long start and removed most of the human planks of wood acting drama then I would say this movie is worth watching multiple times.  But I found the acting to be poorly done and cliche'd (Yeah its a common word that people use when criticise movies but it really shows here and I didn't really enjoy every moment of it).  Good part some actors were really good, the CGI is fantastic, seeing Godzilla in CGI HD really made me want to jump on my theater chair and fucking cheer for Godzilla, he looks that damn good.  The awesome fight scenes were plauged with constant back n forth scenes of constant filler human drama scenes which I wouldn't have mind if the movie kept it short and... well have less human screen time.  When I watch a monster movie I only pay to watch the monster wreck shit up, fight military, fight other monsters and nothing else. The movie did have this but it was too over shadowed by the boring story of the film.  Some people really hate this movie more than I do but I'm not gonna say its "That Bad" but I would never watch this anytime in the future unless a friend of mine wanted to watch a Godzilla marathon.... Which if that did happen would be the fucking bomb.

text: The movie did not do godzilla justice. Godzilla was just BORING, weak, and dull. I also did not want to see the king of monsters defeated by a building? I wasn't just upset that godzilla only fought 10 mins out of the 2 hr movie I waited for, but even the 10 mins godzilla fought was teased and chopped up in between human filler; and the one fight didn't even add up to any 1 fight in the counter kaiju film: Pacific Rim. Godzilla was shot in 3rd person, I wanted more first, second person fighting, better choreographer; building smashing, thrashing, tackeling, or the epic roar the trailer promised but movie didn't deliver. Godzilla did not show any physical damage so it was hard to get really into the action. I'm upset at myself for being disappointed in this movie I built up for several months. He did a couple things but he seemed lazy for being alpha predator 2014.

text: Watched it just yesterday, an OK movie, definitely better than 1998, great effects but too damn dark. I mean, its a movie about a super invincible dinosaur going around blowing stuff up, and they try to make it serious. Back in 1954, when the original came out it was very dark in tone, disturbing and it worked, because the we were still shocked by the power of nuclear weapons, we didnt know much about radiation and it was plausible for some sort of unnatural monstruosity to be created by it, but nowadays you cant take that kind of story seriously, and the origin story for Godzilla in this version is even dumber, which would work much better in a lighter, less serious movie

text: With all respect to all creators of this movie and their attempt to bring old Godzilla back to life - this movie SUCKS ASS! BIG TIME! Its a movie of some plot u dont give a crap not just because of the crappy acting which is on purpose replaced by good one, but because nothing in this movie makes sense. Clearly director wanted to emulate what Nolan or Abrams r capable of but with little success Iam afraid. This isnt believable at all especially in the IMAX where u see all those faces well dressed and their makeup applied on each and every face. And when they add bad acting to it like only Elizabeth Olsen is capable of u know this is not going right direction. On the other hand there r good acting moments like Bryan Cranstons parts who r probably best parts of the movie ;) This guy is a magician, he knows how to be believable but even he was probably asking what the fuck Iam doing here? ;) Anyway to finish this some kind of re-view of this radioactive trash, I have to say that apart from Cranstons acting there r very good moments thx to the well made CG! Yes people, only if there would be more good CG and less bad acting. Sorry David Strathairn u r not admiral, not a fucking chance man! Moments like close encounters with monsters look and sound amazing, only if Godzilla would not scream at people in the cinema for almost 5 seconds. text: I know the point of this kind of movie is action (it did this well), but as someone seeing his first Godzilla movie ever, I thought it was extremely clichéd and formulaic.  It also had a lot of issues...  SPOILERS:  Why the fuck was all the dialogue at the start in the power plant in English? The guy has presumably lived in Japan for some years and is speaking to Japanese people… in Japan. Japanese people rarely speak fluent english. Would he not speak Japanese with his Japanese colleagues? Japanese with subtitles? It's doable guys…  Similarly, when Ford rescues the young Japanese kid, why is he speaking to HIM in English, when he went to a Japanese school and presumably speaks Japanese fluently.   Huge disaster occurs in Japan. Along come the US military: 'we'll take over authority from here.' Wtf? Doesn't Japan have its own government and military with which to respond to this threat/crisis? Why would it just roll over and let superhero America just 'take over'? Classic American movie thinking that 'murica is the centre of the world, a la 'Independence Day' (I still like that movie).  No mention (that I remember) of any kind of international involvement in stopping these giant (alien?) MUTO creatures or huge lizard monster from terrorising the entire world. Wouldn't the leaders of different nations worldwide be in contact? Wouldn't they send their military resources to help? It's cool guys, 'murica will save the day as always.  The scene where the female MUTO breaks out of the nuclear waste bunker thing in Nevada. How the actual fuck did no one notice that before the reveal shot showing the huge hole in the side of the mountain? Did it happen before they went in or during? Wasn't there a… you know… massive fucking crash or something?  Military control room: (I paraphrase) 'civilians still believe it is an earthquake'. Really? Like not one single person had a camera phone or something to leak the news that a giant 20 story high monster has run rampant in Japan? I understand it was meant to be a sealed off area and there were meant to be lots of casualties… but still.  They keep losing track of where the MUTOs are. I'm not an expert on satellites, but wouldn't they all be pointing at them 24/7? Or wouldn't they at least focus on dedicating resources to tracking it, at least from a distance? How do you lose something that huge and destructive in your own country, even for a second?  On a related note, why would you send 2 apocalyptic grade nuclear warheads on a rusty train on a line that you aren't even scouting/securing ahead, knowing full well that it'll attract MUTOs (which you are not keeping track of the movements of). Isn't it somewhat delicate/dangerous cargo? Wouldn't you wanna… like make sure the train line isn't going to be crushed and the warheads somehow detonated in the middle of california? (Hint: people will die)  I'm sure there are more, but the character development and script were dodgy at best. I actually laughed out loud when one of the scientists at the power station monitoring the seismic activity or whatever looks at the reading and goes 'this is worse than we thought'. Also, why does it take bloody Walter White to figure out that it's an electro magnetic pulse being emitted? Seems pretty obvious/detectible. Who are all those guys in lab coats? Extras? Oh wait, that's right.  Killing Walter's (seriously can't remember the guy's character's name, sue me) wife within the first ten minutes of the film is a clumsy attempt at making you emotionally empathetic, when you've had about 2 minutes of screen time to get to know her and you barely know her from a bar of soap. Then Walter himself dies and you're just thinking 'what was that guy even called?'. Conversely, thousands (millions?) of people die right in front of and all around you in the movie and yet you don't really care. Everyone's cheering Godzilla as he swims off into the sunset even though he's presumably responsible for thousands of deaths just with his big stomping feet. It's a bit far fetched to imagine the families of all the dead people actually thinking of him as a good guy, even if he has just effectively saved the planet.   Umm anyone got any more? Basically this movie is shit.

text: I honestly believe people these days are just very impatient and spoiled when it comes to movies these days. People are so use to having explosions pushed into their face every 5 minutes, and they basically expected Pacific Rim 2 but with Godzilla. They get spoon fed all this crap, eat it right up, and then when a really well made movie is crafted, it gets called boring. A damn shame people can't appreciate this movie for what it is.  It's true this movie has its flaws and could've been better than what it was. But flaws aside it was still a well made film with great visuals, cinematography, sound, pacing, with at least serviceable acting. A little more Godzilla screen time and more fleshed out characters and this would have been rated higher for sure.

text: Best Godzilla movie ever! I was so incredibly satisfied I kept smiling for hours after seeing the film. Way better then one could hope for. If you don't know anything about Godzilla, then you may not care for the film. Never saw the 'Bad' Monster in the previews, so was stoked right away when noticing it was the 'Mantis' monster. In the previews it only showed Cranston as the main actor, but was pleased when I realized the soldier was played by the actor who portrayed John Lennon in "No where boy" and Kickass from "Kickass". He did a wonderful job carrying the film. Ken Watanabe continues to do good work. I was pumped when I saw the King of Monsters charge his Atomic Fire. So good. So true to the original creation. He is not just some dinosaur, he doesn't lay eggs. I can only hope for a series of follow ups. Way to go Hollywood! I can't wait to buy some Godzilla gear.

text: I really enjoyed this one, and i'm pretty sure no matter how much I resist the temptation, i'll eventually give in and go see it a second time! It reminds me of JAWS, where the main creature isn't shown until the first half is over. Good ol' days of sheer movie-magic revisited is what this is! Oh, the build-up! The adrenaline-rush from all the spooky sightings that are all at a bare-minimum during that time adds to the whole thrill-kick! The sound department has set a new standard in low-frequency bass-design with this one! I wish this one's DVD also gets a nostalgic throwback to DVDs' Golden Age when she had dts and special features. Remember how wicked the region1 DVD of TWISTER is in terms of it's dts' quality? Yup, a 2-disc special edition would be perfect for good ol' GODZzi! This one's BR better come with dts, and not just dolby digital, else all ye BR folks are gonna be cheated by them greedy studio heads in charge of their beloved titles' home-media release! :-P The 1998 version was just a mindless laugh-riot of a fun summer-ride. Once over ye didn't want to go back for a second round, but ye didn't regret the first ride either, but this one's the kick-in-the-bloomin'-nuts sorta plunge from which ye don't wanna come out! Just fingerlickin' wicked, this here one! Orgasmic-fantastic job, Mr. Edwards! :-D
author: Shijoe Joseph

text: This movie was epic. Any nay sayers probably don't care for godzilla growing up and not using the same gags we saw in the 70s, like....where it had a kid, and started talking.....This movie focused on Godzilla from a human angle. And in the case of something the size that it is, its fair enough to say that if you were immersed in the same situation in real life you'd pretty much be screwed at getting a full on view of everything thats going on too due to random falling buildings. If godzilla had too much screen time in this movie it would have killed it. He'd go from being a titanic beast to a friendly ghost, hell the Muto's started looking pretty weak and un awe inspiring about half way through due to overexposure. In all, everything from the new higher definition roar to the new skin (still keeping him a little chubby, which is nice) was an epic revisit from an old friend. This generation might want 2 hours of non stop monster fighting but get real, they tried that already with the old movies, and it puts people to sleep because godzilla can only do so many tricks in a fight before its the same shit over and over. This movie pays homage to Godzilla in the best way, well worth your money and time, especially if you're a fan of the series.

text: Here's what I think the problem with this Godzilla was;  It honestly felt like it was more like another one of those cookie-cutter apocalyptic military dramas than a revolutionary Godzilla film. Godzilla himself was amazing, but he felt more like a guest star in his own movie. Be honest with yourselves, who actually goes to a Godzilla movie for sluggish, over-saturated human/ military drama? This is where I think Edwards made a huge mistake with this movie...this is NOT a remake of the original 1954. I don't know why people are trying to justify the severe lack of screen time Godzilla had because of what the original was like. Godzilla was new back then. The mystery was interesting. This is a reboot 60 years in the future. You have a different audience. The standards are higher. On top of that, there was endless speculation for YEARS when this project was announced, regarding what he was going to look like, how big he was going to be, who, or what he was going to fight..among many other things. You are recreating on of, if not arguably the most iconic movie monster of all time. And it just didn't deliver. I'm not saying it needs monster brawls every 10 minutes like Pacific Rim and such, but when you've got a movie like this that suggests it, you've got to have SOME free-for-all carnage spaced out on the occasion.  I understand he wanted anticipation and suspense, like in Alien, Jaws, and Jurassic Park. But something I felt Edwards forgot about those films, is when it was time for show the monster/ alien/ Godzilla thing, they GAVE you the monster and they actually DID something and had an iconic scene. And if you look most of the time the scenes weren't even that action-driven at all. Look at Jurassic Park; when they built up the suspense for the T-rex, they started by only showing bits of the Rex. Then when it was time to show of the T-rex, they GAVE you the T-rex. Did he start devouring the characters right away? No, we got a terrifying scene where he stalks the kids in the car. And it worked. Same thing with the raptor/ kitchen scene. They didn't just go berserk and start clawing at everything, no they set up a suspensful stalking scene yet still successfully portrayed the character of the creature. But these movies are also supported with powerful characters. Godzilla lacked this entirely. It got frustrating to watch after the first tease. Again, not because he wasn't engaged in a destructive fight scene, but because they kept cutting away from him without actually giving him anything to do. So for those of you who think the ones who desired more screen time on Godzilla's end just wanted endless monster brawls, you're wrong. Well, that's the way I saw it.

text: SPOILERS!!! Some reasons why this movie was a disappointing mess: Point one - Juliette Binoche almost gets as much screen-time as Godzilla.  Point two - Tokyo doesn't get so much as a scratch and Godzilla, as everyone knows, should have a special craving for smashing up Japan.  Point three - Starship troopers and Cloverfield both want their shitty monster designs back.  Point four - since when does Godzilla give a fuck about human beings?  Point five - either be totally implausible or totally serious; DON'T try to do both and treat your audience with contempt.  Point six - a monster movie is about big things; don't show me mediocre melodrama, show me MONSTERS, in particular the monster whose name is all over the advertisements.  Point seven - Hiding behind the banner of 'heightening dramatic tension' does not excuse the filmmakers trampling all over the growing excitement of the audience as Godzilla gets revealed, only to be hidden away for another 30 minutes.  In fact, audience expectation was the only thing that got seriously trampled in this film.  Just not good enough!
author: George Morley

text: To the people talking about Jaws and "slow-reveals" and all that stuff, I would say this:   What makes Jaws scary?  It's a film about a killer shark.  What makes killer sharks scary?  You don't know when they will strike and you can't see them most of the time, because they are in the water.  Therefore, a slow reveal worked perfectly for Jaws.    However, this is not Jaws.  This is a Godzilla movie.  Godzilla movies aren't about slow reveals.  Godzilla is the size of an African republic.  You could see him coming if you were on Mars.  What Godzilla films should be about is trashing Tokyo.  As this did not take place, I contend that this movie was shit.  And that Japanese kid that got lost on the train got more screen time than Godzilla.  I hated it.  Only in my opinion, you understand.  Just mine, and thousands of other people's opinions.    Oh and the makers of Cloverfield and Starship troopers both want their shitty rejected monster designs back now they're finished with.
author: George Morley

text: Don't know why this gets a lot of dislikes. The movie was actually pretty damn good, with some of the best CGI I've seen. I dislike excessive amounts of CGI in things that do not need it (i.e Hobbit), but anyone complaining about it in a project such as Godzilla is laughable. What do people want them to do, dress someone in a suit? Please no. The CGI in this movie is definitely warranted and VERY well done. This movie was visually stunning, my favorite being the parachute scene which you see in the trailer, coupled with music that was frightening and dramatic in a very good way on the big screen. The monsters didn't look fake or overdone or like they were wrapped in plastic wrap, something many movies suffer from these days. They looked raw and real. Godzilla actually looked like Godzilla. I'm no expert on the original movies, but they seem to have stuck with the original design very well.  Many scenes were often beautiful and eerie. Very good cinematography. As far as music, there were times when there was almost too much music when there shouldn't have been, but when the good scores came, they were masterfully done and placed. Very nice suspense, too. It reminded me much of the far more subtle Monsters, by the same director.  Granted, much of the plot and human stories could have used work and it's not a title that will leave you questioning the workings of human kind. I wish it had revolved around Bryan Cranston's character and his young son instead. That said, it does seem to be delivering the message that we really shouldn't act as if we have control over mother nature, which was nice. I'll add that one thing I really liked a lot is that there was no usage of good vs. evil in the people. There was no sour, vengeful, overdone egotistical jackass ruining everything like you see in so many movies. And the main human protagonist lacked that cocky "I'm the shit," attitude you see a lot of these days. Everyone was, well, HUMAN. They were all scared, confused and while there were disagreements between characters here and there (all natural and understandable arguments, thankfully), there wasn't that one guy acting like it was his way or the highway. Huge breath of fresh air, right there. 7/10

text: People who are asking for more Godzilla are just people who want a mindless blockbuster. People who are saying that Godzilla is in it for less then 10 minutes.... Complete and utter bullshit. I watched this movie twice and the second was better then the first time because I realized that Gareth Edwards was basically setting up a potential sequel and/or trilogy. It's an origin story. Do not expect to see Godzilla that much (even though he was in it for more then enough time). The Mutos were the main focus of the movie. Clear as day. Everyone wanted to see them because the trailers gave hints and quick looks at what they are. But when the movie comes out they get pissed off by the amount of time they had compared to Godzilla. There's no pleasing you people. People complain about how Pacific Rim had absolutely no interesting characters and just being a monster mash-up with a less then stellar plot, but when a movie comes out like Godzilla, who has interesting characters like Bryan Cranston and Ken Wantanabe, people get butthurt with Godzilla not being in the movie and not having monster fights. Gareth Edwards has stated that he didn't want a CGI fest. He did a great job on teasing Godzilla and when he arrived, it was a beautiful sight. He did not over-saturate the movie with monsters. The movie was paying homage to the original Godzilla movies. He did the series a major justice. And best of all, the movie is successful in the box office. We are getting a sequel. He we setting this movie up to be the first in a line of Godzilla movies. We now know what Godzilla is. The sequels will be great movies.  And I'm not saying that Godzilla didn't have flaws. All movies have flaws. The movie for me is a 9/10 because it revived Godzilla and most of all, gave him personality. The movie is an excellent show case on how the Kaiju genre is being revived. Just you people can never be pleased. And to those who are listening and reading these comments saying Godzilla is barely in the movie, the acting is terrible and all of that bullshit, they can not be more wrong. ATJ was a little stale, but he played the stereotypical Navy Lieutenant. The rest of the characters were solid. Please, do not listen to these comments. The movie was not boring at all. If you listen to these comments, you will be missing out on an absolutely fantastic movie. As a life long Godzilla fan, this movie exceeded my expectations and then some. It was a perfect DaiKaiju film.

text: It kept cutting away from fight scenes (which was so frustrating) and we never got to see the initial destruction of the city. Plus the most interesting character (Bryan Cranston) got killed off quickly, while the protagonist the writers decided to go with was bland and uninteresting to watch (especially when you know there's a kaiju fight going on in the background somewhere.) The fight at the end was also over far too quickly.  I was really underwhelmed by this. I really wanted to like it, but it was so frustrating to watch. The way it builds up to a fight scene and then cuts away to the human characters was a terrible idea and really took away from the excitement.

text: I was one of the people who worked on this movie, and I gotta say, the monsters did an amazing job.  They were the nicest eldritch abominations this side of Rl'yeh, but when that camera started rolling, man, it was like they became something else. Off-screen they told jokes, had casual conversations with the crew, Andy (Male MUTO) was thrilled to meet Bryan Cranston (he's a big Malcolm in the Middle fan) and Margery (Female MUTO) could barely stay away from Aaron. But seriously, the guy who had the most fun was the Big Man himself. He tried to keep it in, but he just couldn't hide how happy he was to be a part of a big production again. He may be in his sixties, but he acted just like a school boy. I actually got to briefly talk with him for a bit and among our shit-shooting, we talked about his cousin Zilla. Apparently after his big break out movie flopped, he fell into a bit of a depression but is better now. Unfortunately the monsters couldn't make it to the premier (the theatre was too small), but apparently they were happy with how the film turned out, and the Big Man said he's more than game to return for a sequel! I hear that a certain other King might be in it!

text: Why do the fanboys that defend this movie act like it wasn't advertising giant monsters? I mean what do you think people want to see when they go see movies about giant monsters, anyway? "If you want to see monster battles go watch Pacific Rim, or the other Godzilla movies." What a shitty excuse for an argument. Please don't bullshit yourselves into believing you actually enjoyed the cardboard human drama that overpowered 80% of this movie. You want to watch human drama? That's what CSI, Law & Order and the like are for. I love Godzilla movies, I really do. But I'm sorry, but this was hardly a Godzilla movie. And to be completely honest, I even found the 98 Zilla more entertaining. And that movie is horrible, but ya know what? At least when it was shitty, it was honest, and it kept me somewhat entertained, and didn't cheat me out into believing I was going to see a monster that ended up playing an insignificant role IN HIS OWN MOVIE. Godzilla 2014 was better in the sense of paying homage to the original, but failed miserably to live up to the potential it could've had. Especially with all the speculation that went into it for the what, 3-4 years this project was announced prior to the final release?  And it wasn't even the lack of Godzilla fighting that made this movie frustrating to watch, it was the lack of Godzilla doing anything at all. He could have been interacting with something, or someone. Building anticipation of the beast is one thing, but the constant cock-teasing got stupidly old. The first tease was fine. But after that, he would show up, roar, and get abruptly cut off without him doing anything memorable. Until the last 10 minutes...and even that kept getting cut off.  Call me out on it fanboys, but as shitty as it was 98 Zilla kept me more entertained. Thing is, I wanted to like this 2014 film more, but it just didn't deliver what it advertised. I paid 18 bucks to see Godzilla, not another dime a dozen apocalyptic military/ family drama. There are 200+ channels worth of that stuff on TV already. Good monster movies are rare anymore these days. Godzilla had so much potential to set a new standard, but fell flat of anything substantial. Hopefully the sequels will redeem this movie's flaws.

text: What's the best & worst movie you've seen in 2014 so far?  [ SPOILERS ]   Worst - Godzilla  I went in with high expectations but damn what a letdown this movie was. The trailer is probably one of the most well done trailer ever made that makes you think " wow this is gonna be so epic & there is no way this movie will be a letdown " but like srsly. Also the trailer is hella misleading, it makes you think Godzilla is the actual threat, but no it's the Mutos. Ye, those are gonna send us back to stone age. -.- Mutos got more screen time than Godzilla. They probably should have just called this movie Muto. The first half is a bore fest. In fact, things don't really pick up until about 90 minutes in. Every time you think a fight is going to happen the movie just cuts to something else. I was astounded. It wasn't even the lack of Godzilla fighting that made this movie boring to watch, it was the lack of Godzilla doing anything at all.   If you like drama + alot of side stories and 5 minutes of action then this is the right movie for you! Ye, I am kinda angry now since I am a huge Godzilla fan, but this movie was a huge disappointment. The biggest disappointment I have seen so far this year. What was the director thinking while making this movie?   Best - Edge of Tomorrow  I went in with low expectations and came out speechless. Hell I am not a Tom Cruise fan and tbh I don't like his movies at all, but this movie was so good - words can't even describe how epic this movie is. You have to see it to know what's up lol. No srsly, in case you haven't seen it yet, go and see it! The trailer was kinda " ye hm looks like a decent movie with some cool special effects and explosions " but it's so much better than this.   I don't wanna spoil anything here lol, just go and see it yourself. For me this is not only the best movie of 2014 so far, but one of the top 10 movies I have seen all time.  IMO

text: My favorite movie of the year. I loved how old school this movie was... I see a lot of people complaining, not action, not enough Godzilla, etc. Those are valid opinions. If you're looking for a modern not stop action style blockbuster this movie isn't for you. If you're looking for something that actually takes it's time building and even has quitter moments in it then this movie is very rewarding. I do really think the audience has forgotten how to watch movies. Since CGI has taken over special effects, a lot of movies through anything and everything at you because they can. There was a time when special effects movies simply couldn't do that. It used to be actually difficult to bring a giant monster to life on screen, so film makers were forced to be creative. For my money the movies were better for it. Godzilla 2014 is a rare modern film that harkens back to those older films.

text: This was a great movie despite Godzilla's limited screen time. Anyone saying that the movie was just downright terrible because of it is just being melodramatic. Could the film have benefitted by having a few more scenes with Godzilla? Yes. Was it bad because it didn't? Absolutely not.  That said, I will admit that waiting an hour for Godzilla's reveal and then immediately switching back to Ford's perspective was a poor choice on the director's part. And I would have liked to see Godzilla at least attack the military in self-defense. But as I said, the movie wasn't bad by any sense of the word.

text: some people hate it some people love it. i find it.... OK. its not what you would call a standard, classic Godzilla film, but it does have its perks. it has more people than Godzilla, which i found annoying because for most of the movie, the humans don't do anything. the bomb goes off in the ocean because their original "this bomb is bigger so it will kill them" plan didn't work, nearly all of the characters could have been left out, and i had more of an emotional attachment to the MUTOS bomb / mating scene (which was adorable) than i did with the main character and his wife and child. however, the scenes with Godzilla and the MUTOS are freaking awesome. the MUTOS look like a combination of Orga, Rodan, Clover field, and the star ship troopers bugs. Godzilla looked amazing (but his feet looked a little silly) and he was huge. his atomic breath was not as... well... atomic, as it normally blows up anything it hits, and at the end of the scene where Godzilla melts the insides of the female MUTOS (which was awesome), i was expecting a minty fresh breath gum advertisement to pop up at the bottom. i still enjoyed it and it delivered what i expected for an american reboot of Godzilla. (this was a ton better than that 1998 iguana we got.)  Like it or hate it, this movie does prove one simple fact: GODZILLA COULD WHIP CLOVER FIELD'S ASS ANY DAY!!! (because clover field and the female MUTOS are basically the same thing.)

text: This movie was almost a total letdown. Did not live up to either the hype of its trailers or the legacy of the Toho films it was supposed to take after. It ripped off too many clichés from Jurassic Park, featured too little of either the monsters or Bryan Cranston; the backstory was poorly set up, there was effectively zero buildup of tension through the plot, and none of the characters (besides Cranston's) were convincing. It had its shining moments, but unfortunately, these did not make up for the other flaws in the film. I was expecting this to be The Dark Knight among Godzilla films, but no....

text: Everyone hates on the new Godzilla film, even though everyone's favorite Godzilla movie, Destroy All Monsters, cuts to news casts and scientists about 80% of the damn movie. Rodan, Gorosaurus, and Godzilla have been unleashed on the world - we see Rodan fly ONCE, then Gorosaurus roar, then it cut's to a 7 minute recap of everything. "Godzilla has appeared in. New York!" - cuts to Godzilla, Spikes light up and he heads inland, breathing fire one time, he moves closer to shore, aaaannndd . . . NEWS CASTER TALKING ABOUT IT. Godzilla, Manda, Mothra and Rodan attack Tokyo - Mothra crawls for a sec, Godzilla crushes about 3 buildings, Rodan flys and does nothing, Manda destroys train track, tanks shoot for a sec - SCIENTISTS. In between it had people talking, and doing random stuff and I appreciated it, so did everyone else. I appreciated it in this movie, why can't anyone else do that now. Btw, this movie has a 22 minute climax, counting the halo jump, godzilla vs muto, human nuke scenea, and ending. Godzilla has, jumbled with the human nuke cuts and hawaii scene, (which was 11 minutes) he has about 43 minutes of time dedicated to his character. Destroy All Monsters has an 11 minute finale, a 6 minute destruction scene, about 2 minutes of news footage, and another 3 minutes of destruction. Just appreciate this 2014 movie as the king's return!

text: ENOUGH!! Time for me to show why this movie wasn't good for half of us whose seen it, now brace yourselves for my humongous paragraph of why we don't like the new godzilla movie:  I'm sure people who's never seen Godzilla before could maybe enjoy this movie, but if you're a true godzilla fan or you're just smart, then you could see the problems with this movie as well. Like seriously, we get a movie that has almost no purpose with godzilla being in there at all, and with the show being stolen by the Mutos (the other monsters in this movie) and humans, like seriously the title's called godzilla but the conflict in this movie is "How we gonna stop them Mutos?" And no don't mistaken me into complaining that there wasn't that much godzilla in the movie, that's not really the problem here, my problem is that nothing really in this movie actually fulfilled enough to make it feel like a godzilla movie, seriously I thought this movie was a joke. Like 35 minutes through the movie until they actually start talking about godzilla, then he just appears out of nowhere to fight the muto, but still he wasn't really that much of a concern, instead he was just being used in this movie to help beat the Mutos. Also, all that teasing? I'm sure Gareth Edwards, the director, wasn't screwing around with us, but don't any if you feel like he was? Good teasing of godzilla until they finally show his whole body, then they cut him off to humans because oh yeah humans are more important to show in this movie called godzilla, and then we get a stupid 11 seconds fight scene. Then they show godzilla again like another 45 minutes later, but they've already shown godzilla fully but now they still feel like teasing his body parts, very unnecessary, we already saw godzilla, why are they trying to hide him again like it's suppose to be a surprise? Oh yeah, Ford Brody, or Aaron johnson, not very good at acting in this movie, he showed very low emotion to the type of situation going on in this film and he was very, very noncarable. And seriously, HE WAS THE MAIN CHARACTER IN THIS MOVIE?? HAHAHAHA he's the main guy here but in the beginning of the movie they built up much more of Bryan Cranstons character to actually make us care more about him. Then he dies so early but that also means his character build up was all for NOTHING, seriously, that means that whole 15 minutes in the beginning of movie was useless and we watched that part for no reason since Cranston wasn't even the main character and he died off almost right after a good character build up. How awesome is that? Then the rest of the movie we get stuck with Aaron Johnson with such boring talking scenes that are also useless, and more boring characters, except Ken Watanabe, and then we get the awesome looking fight scene that we were all waiting for, then nope it cuts back to human conflict. Cuts back to monsters fighting, then cuts back to humans. Cuts back to monsters, then cuts to humans, AGAIN. Then we get the atomic breath, which is super weak and looks like a fire breath, which is not even what he shoots, which means people who aren't familiar with godzilla will now think that godzilla just shoots blue fire, which is very incorrect. I would most likely look at godzillas atomic breath as like a bomb, you know, when it impacts the ground then powerful explosions will happen, just like the godzillas in the 2000s. And um a lot of you also love how the movie ended, I don't. There's not really a reason why, it's just that I didn't feel good about that ending, and that they were wondering if godzilla is their savior. Oh yeah about that godzilla is the savior of the city thing, remember the trailers would always refer to godzilla as like "It can't be stopped" or idk just being destructive? Yeah, well idk I just don't see godzilla as a good guy you know, I know he used to be a good guy in past movies, but remaking godzilla in a more serious manner doesn't seem like that's how he's suppose to be portrayed. Well nothing is for sure yet if he is going to be a good guy, but I hope not. So there you have it, why I don't like the new godzilla movie, and holy god King Ghidorah's my favorite godzilla kaiju and seriously he better not be screwed up in the next movie.

text: Goddammit, this film is SHIT!  First of all, with the exception of Bryan Cranston (Walter White, bitch!), who's far too good to be in this drivel, all the other actors are either complete unknowns or ones that you would never in your worst nightmare wish to see in a film like this.  Juliette Binoche belongs in boring costume dramas and obscure French indie films. Ken Watanabe is an OK dramatic actor, but here, all he does is look constipated and say things in closeup like: "We call it...GOJIRA!"  Sally Hawkins is a superb actress, but she doesn't fit the American or Japanese stereotype her role requires. She's absurdly miscast.  Which leaves us with Aaron Taylor-Johnson, the most blank-faced. vapid asshole the silver screen has punished us with since Botox was invented. Not that Aaron has injected Botox into his face. But if he did, he might actually be able to express more than simply mild confusion (hmm...what is 2+2?).  I had hopes (for a while) that things would turn out OK. I mean, Bryan Cranston typically gives his pathetic role his ALL. But fuck you, movie, he doesn't last long. And neither does Juliette Binoche. And suddenly we're supposed to root for Taylor-Johnson as our hero?  HAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAa hA!!!!  And then we have the horrible special effects. Honestly, I sat there thinking "What does this remind me of?". The effects looked unbelievably cheap and unconvincing for such a mega-budget affair, and I've honestly seen better work done by people on their home computers.  My mind drifted back to 2010. One of my most hated films of that year was Monsters. A fucking boring, pretentious piece of shit, in which the director and his girlfriend were running around, hiding from barely seen monsters, when they weren't being in looove.  Now, the effects in Monsters were made by the director himself, on his home computer, so that's why I thought of that film. Gareth Edwards, his name was.  I went to IMDB. Who's the director of Godzilla? Gareth FUCKING Edwards!  Honestly, dick-face, stop making films RIGHT NOW! You make Shite Shyamalan's crap look good!

text: Ya know, I loved this movie. I loved how they made him savior/destroyer. However, in my opinion the marketing peeps made a bitch move by having the first trailers show Godzilla as an unstoppable force against mankind. Its as if they wanted to target pop-corn action movie goers when the film itself was structured on "controlled" suspense and build up. This was not an all-out action extravaganza and it was not meant to be. This was a Godzilla movie for the fans. The point is, I understand some of the negative criticism on differences from the trailers (except the Asian trailer, which was the most honest). I knew what to expect because I followed it closely and was not let down. There were allot of people who saw the first few trailers and said; "No more, I'm already sold and I don't want any spoilers". They had their expectations set and the film did indeed turn out a bit different. I hate it when marketing for anything is handled that way. Unless you are a trollish figure who hates the movie because it was a success, I understand your reasoning for not liking the film.

text: Yes the movie had some flaws, but be a good person on the internet for once and show pros and cons bitches.  Pros: -Face it, amazing CGI -Very good sound design all around, good music, some of the best moments were Godzilla's roars -Build up makes for a good/epic last battle -Bryan Cranston some good scenes with Aaron Taylor Johnson -An over solid plot, Godzilla origin wise/science wise  Cons: -Weak human story at some parts -Lags off at some parts -No truly intense action until 40 minute mark (I checked on that) -I am not complaining here that Bryan Cranston died in the movie, it's really just that he kept the human drama going, and you can see that after him with just Elizabeth Olson and Aaron, it fades away.  And lastly the dialogue was a mixed bag. Maybe it was the dialogue that muddled the human drama, but some moments with the scientists and military and what not had solid dialogue and interesting things to hear. So there you go, a real review instead of infinite praise or down right not giving the movie a chance. I did see it in IMAX, and yes that did make me love it, but I also saw it on DVD, which although still shows the good CGI and what not, doesn't give the experience Godzilla went out to give. So there you go, internet arguing commense.

text: This movie was spectacular. I respect everyone's opinion, but in my own, and as a die hard Godzilla fan, I can't see how people disliked it. First off, the acting and characters were not that forgettable or bland at all. Aaron Taylor Johnson played a military character trying to get back to his family. Mission first, emotion later. Bryan Cranston was fantastic and his death was justified, he served no further purpose in the plot after that point. Elizabeth Olson's interaction with her son was great. That first scene between Joe Brody, and his wife dying was heart wrenching. I'm not even going to get into the cinematography because it was damn perfect. And in the original 1954 film, Godzilla is in there for a good 20 minutes. The point was to build suspense, create a terrifying atmosphere and make you wait for that great action, which is what this movie pulled off perfectly. Our generation is so accustomed to Michael Bay style storytelling with things blowing up twenty four seven and that just loses the tingle. Also, there was plenty of Muto destruction and appearance throughout, so I can't see how you were bored during. But that's just my opinion.

text: The reason why Godzilla got less than 20 min. of screen time is: 1. Most of the other Godzilla movies has up to 15-20 min. of Godzilla time, BUT a lot of the other monsters scenes, especially this one, theirs 20+ of MUTO scenes. Also the movies that has more than half of the movie having Godzilla in it, is rather one of the worse (Godzilla's Revenge) or good-one of the best (Godzilla: Final Wars). 2. It's a build up. It builds suspense for the FINAL battle which was smart. If you saw it in 3D it looked like crap because it took place at night and 3D glasses and movies make things more blurry and kinda ruins the movie. Also 3D movies vacuum's your wallet. Also, if it showed every single fight scene, the movie would've been spoiled. 3. Audiences today are soo used to seeing non-stop action and explosions being in the movie more than the story (I'm looking at you Michel Bay), that it's starting to become a necessity. It's kinda showing how stupid people are getting. This is a gear change that should be in other movies so audiences can start focusing on story's or plot and less about the action and fight scenes.

text: I think most people's opinion on the movie depends on what their expectations were, for example I was very hyped, I followed the release for this movie for long before the movie came out, I knew about the MUTO, I knew that Godzilla wouldn't appear until halfway through the movie. So when I saw it, it blew my mind away. I don't like that people say there was no action, there was plenty of action spread out through the movie to keep people entertained, it's not just two hours of people talking. There are action scenes like the Janjira Powerplant, the MUTO escape, the Hawaii build up, the railway scene Godzilla at the bridge, and of course the final battle. Godzilla appears 57 minutes into the movie, which is usual for an origin story, and after that, he appears 25 minutes later, in between those 25 minutes there is the railway scene and the Las Vegas scene, and after it there is the final battle which is about 25-30 minutes long. So the last half of the movie there definitely is a lot of action. The first half only has two action scenes, so if you can be patient for the first half of the movie and let the anticipation build, you will be pleased. Oh, and another note the Muto appears 35 minutes into the film, so that means approximately every 20 minutes there is an exciting scene. So it is not boring. To those who haven't seen the movie, don't let the haters take control of your opinion create one of your own, it's a very fun movie.

text: This movie splits people, but I rather liked it. I've seen it multiple times now and can really say I enjoyed my time with it, my favourite blockbuster from this summer. If you didn't, that's fine, but it was a nice change of pace from all the action films we've seen, which think they have to have an explosion every five minutes to keep people interested in it, like dangling your keys in front of a baby. And I don't think it's possible to think this is the worst Godzilla movie ever made, neither do I think the 98 movie is, not even close. When stuff like "Godzilla's Revenge" exists, it's hard to go lower than that. And the 1998 Godzilla in all it's crappiness, was at least technically somewhat a functional movie, which is no praise, it was still horrible in every respect. This one I really really liked. The scarce use of Godzilla was good for this, because it's the introduction, they were just starting this up. In the next movie, I'd like to see more Godzilla, but still keep it smart and "conservative" compared to movies like Pacific Rim and other basic blockbusters. I have complete trust in Gareth, he has proven himself to be a capable director and knows how to make a good Godzilla movie.

text: The lack of Godzilla for much of it was fine, it was the human parts that didn't add up + the director kept pulling the rug from out under us every time we think we are going to see Godzilla bring on the pain (he does, but we just don't see it >:() until the end)  Would have made movie far more interesting film if Bryan Cranston's son died instead of him and we followed this character as he tries to seek both meaning and revenge for what this "white whale" of a beast did to him twice now. Tries to satisfy this need while running crossroads with the Ken Watanabe and the military's operation to contain what is all going on. This could provide some good character interactions and even square-offs between two men of science who have both lost much to great beasts (Cranston the mothra thing, Watanabe: Godzilla for example, by giving him some background where Godzilla was responsible somehow in their efforts to contain him in the past having cost Watanabe dearly somehow.) Watanabe is more paragon and has achieved peace with what he has lost at this point in his life, turning to study Godzilla and having accepted that what happened was nothing personal to him anymore that it could be with a force of nature (Maybe Watanabe loses someone dearly to him from radiation fallout, having to watch that person die horribly and sorrowfully from a fruitless attempt to control nature essentially, by trying to kill Godzilla simply out of fear back then, was greatly wounded and hateful as a result of it and even blamed Godzilla for it all happening, but in time in his past efforts to learn about him to destroy him, comes to understand that it was mans overreaction to the neutral, but awesome creature that caused the loss and not Godzillas. Bringing more weight to his line later in the film on 'man thinking they can control nature') and is now focused on trying to help the military stop what is going down with the mothra-thing. While Cranston is still fresh in his pain (his sons adding to it) and wants to see the mothra-thing dead at any cost. Eventually you could still have a similar scenario with the ticking nuke in the clutches of the mothra-mother-thing and Cranston finding himself in a situation where he could either let it blow up and kill everyone still stuck in the city in revenge or listen to Watanabe's wisdom from prior dialogue exchanges and put his hate aside and try and help the last remaining paratroopers sent in to disarm it and get it out and disabled for the sake of the city. Cranston does and Godzilla shows up (again) and kills the mothra-mother-thing as it pursues Cranston and what soldiers are left, in a way avenging Cranston on his behalf as Godzilla counters the massivve imbalance that were the two MUTO. In the end Cranston not only frees himself from the hate and suffering from his deep losses, but in turn learns some humility for the forces of nature and accepts that it can take as well as it can give. Hell I don't know how to end it totally, I guess the way it did in the film. Irregardless, I like to try and guess the basic plot of a movie before I go see it and this is what I thought it would be like. Oh well.  Sorry for the messy post, I'm just spilling thoughts out here.

text: Not that I'm being a Trollinator BUT BUT I just finished another poem - this is the LONGEST POEM I have yet written and the longest yet I took to write (well took just under 2 months to get all the ideas and concepts) about BIG-G GODZILLA (with references to Big-G 2014 and previous Big-G incarnations - some parts may be repeats but I thought it fits in just like lyrics haha - enjoy - but its about 10K words long haha)   Call me a ‘Goji-saur’, Call me a ‘Tyrannosaur’, Call me the ‘Ancient Dinosaur’, Once a Godzillasaur,  An Ancient Dinosaur, Towering hundreds or more, Scarred with Ancient Wars, The more I lived to Score, Long in the years, I was your worst fears, Yet when the roar you hear I be rumbling closer, Doom be near …   Legacy of the Palaeozoic, Hero of the Mesozoic, The King of the Prehistoric, The King of the Monsters, The Alpha Predator, Alas, I be no Terminator, I was but the Predator Alpha, My Reign would spread across Continents Terra, The Power I would Gain …from the Foes I’d Slain…  The night sky shone so bright, Yet be not star, Around the worlds and yet to lands yet so far, The sea shone so glow, Yet this was no fantasy foretold, For this glow, Alas be Death’s glow, The Atomic blow, I would not slow, Yet the aura that glows, The rage that grows, The World shall know, Alas, Nuclear Power … the World shall know…  From 1954-2014, The 6 Decades between, Alas each Decade ending in a four, Each sequel more colossal than before, For every Kaiju’s War, Would mark my Atomic Score, For Tokyo I Smashed! Nagoya I Crashed! Osaka I Trashed! Even San Francisco where the MUTO’s I Thrashed! Nowhere in the World it safe … from my Atomic Dash!  Be a glow! A flash! A flare! Or my very glare!  In the misbegotten street of misery, a light A hellish flash, and hellish sight A roar that scored! The Hellish Shrieks beyond the Freaks!  For I enclose my steps upon the Streets…  The blasts! The screams! The terror! A Kaiju’s War! For the metals shoot and fall, Yet with a dull clang … I yet still stand so tall, For no mere fortified wall, Could truly stall I defy Mankind’s Very Laws, Yet I would never truly fall, For prepare … for the Kaiju’s Grand Brawl…  I could make you mournful, You could mock me scornful, I could be marked awful, Yet you never could make me hurtful, For you piss me off … my rage proves me dreadful …   My foes retreat or die …  Yet I could laugh, I could cry, Yet be that buildings fall by their halls, With a stroke and a strike, Yet worst than the thunder strike! Another toppling, by my all sweeping tail, Oh be it a true tale … that you’d tell …  A fire! Fire! Smoke through the Streets, A Skreeonk to Beat! The Atomic Screech! Burns all it Creeps, The Great Tail, strikes all it sweeps…  On your news you hear, Reporting your deepest fear, Doom leers so near, So soon strike the rear, I destroy all you held so dear, My roar deafens your ear …   A clang or, a melody of Devastation, Miles of Destruction! The Endless Invasion! The Mindless Sensation, Alas! The melody of Destruction …  As I hurl obstacles aside, Cities I wreck astride, I care not what I flip aside … be it cars, beings and buildings, The Destruction … of Mankind’s Findings… A Radiation Sickness!  It radiates Despair in the crowd For soon your city … envelopes …  In a deadly mound of pity...  An silent eerie.  After the agony and pains.  None of the city remains, Nor will your pity be any gains, Only endless rain, Of Endless Atomic Nuclear Pain … A NUCLEAR WARRIOR! THE ATOMIC SAVIOR! text: Where is this huge pile of haters everyone is writing about, I don't know. Just look at the like-dislike rate before jumping into conclusions and start whining (ironic that you accuse others of that, btw). Well, yh, I know that most didn't like it but to say that there are many "haters", is just not true.  Since I started typing I'm gonna go ahead and say it, in case you didn't guess it already :p Yes, I am one of those who think this movie was just... pointless. I actually could tell by watching the trailer and, if it wasn't for the lack of a better movie (at least according to that friend of mine) I wouldn't have wasted time and money that day and, instead, I would have seen a movie I liked for real, a few weeks or months later. Well, it's true, there wasn't any movie I definitely wanted to see at that time :/ Whatever, what's done is done, and I will watch every movie that has made it on my list eventually, just not in theaters.   Honestly, I'm not saying these to hate on anyone... but yh, I suppose that everyone who loves(!) the new Godzilla is too young to have a solid experience of good movies, or is simply tasteless and/or incapable of judging objectively. To elaborate a bit... it's mainly that it's so full of silly cliches. And nothing particularly exciting happens. That Tyranitar shooting Hyper Beams near the end only made it worse for me, I mean... just why? :s and this scene overshadowed anything remotely good this movie had to offer (I tried to be less negative about it, but I couldn't help it... especially after that part).

text: This film, shot by shot, is a retelling of Rudyard Kipling's _Rikki-Tikki-Tavi_.  A house plagued by a mated pair of snakes is entered by a mongoose, who by default hunts an animal that is a threat to man and is such the 'hero'. Tracking them down, he fights the male cobra first and kills him, while the unhatched eggs are destroyed before they produce more snakes. This incites the rage of the grieving female, who tries to take revenge by killing the young boy, the main human character, but is saved by the mongoose. The mongoose, by simply being a predator, is hailed a hero and returns to his home, now in good terms with the humans as a pet-protector.  Now replace Rikki the mongoose with our favorite atomic lizard and the cobras with the MUTOs. I knew the story seemed familiar...

text: I'm going to compensate for all of you and say why this movie is AWESOME: 1. Amazing special effects. 2. Serious tone makes you feel like you're a part of it and emphasizes realistic-feeling aftermath. 3. Amazingly shot- integrates CG elements with real elements so beautifully. 4. Great score 5. Works as a crescendo from start to finish. 6. Godzilla kills the monsters in really badass ways. 7. Fantastic, convincing Production design, sets, and huge military involvement 8. Camera usually from a human perspective, immersive and emphasizes the scale 9. Awesome new origin story for these monsters (Better than- oh radiation created these ridiculous creatures, which makes no sense, Emmerich didn't bother to change)                                                                                                                                                 10. The military is a peace-keeping force that makes a genuine mistake, no belligerent generals or asshole-ish mayors. 11. Convincing performances                                                                                                                                                                   Bryan Cranston- Wife died, isolated and looking for answers Elizabeth Olson- Worried wife and mother Aaron Taylor Johnson- A soldier doing his job in the middle of intense shit. "Wooden" - or realistic soldier?  If you weren't drawn in, thrilled, in awe and at the edge-of-your-seat, then I pity you because movies like this don't come along very often.

text: This movie is both a gift and a curse. Despite conflicting reviews, many of the films strongest elements, from its direction, cinematography, visual effects, creature designs, sound design, and seemingly serious tone, were just enough to win many fans over. Had it not been for this movie, Toho probably wouldn't have come back to make "Godzilla 2016," let alone let Rodan, Mothra, and King Ghidorah be included in the sequels. As far as I know, it can only go up from here for the franchise.  On a bad day, I think this movie is living proof that Hollywood still thinks Godzilla fans are completely and utterly worthless. But on a good day, this movie is a treasured milestone that encompasses how far I've come as a lifelong fan. One that I'll always cherish as a nostalgic memory.  Hail to the king, baby!

text: This is, by far, my favorite movie of 2014, and I saw a lot of movies! The story was creative, and very much like a classic Godzilla story. The characters and acting were all great, especially from Ken Watanabe and Bryan Cranston. Gareth Edwards did a fantastic job directing. The action scenes were all tense, exciting, and beautifully filmed! The score was awesome. And finally, the film payed huge respect to the classic Japanese Godzilla films, which I am a huge fan of! I saw this twice in the theater, and I happily placed the dvd next to my Godzilla movie collection! This movie was to me the perfect Godzilla movie! It proved that an American version of Godzilla could still be done correctly, even after the disaster from 1998! It is a great addition to the Godzilla franchise, and a great movie on it's own! Best movie of 2014 in my opinion! Can't wait for the sequel in 2018!
