text: Godzilla is a 2014 American science fiction monster film directed by Gareth Edwards and a reboot of Toho's Godzilla franchise. The film is set mostly in the present day, fifteen years after a discovery that leads to the awakening of two giant creatures, known as "MUTOs", who in turn awaken a much much much much much much more larger, more indistrcible, more bigger and badder more terriofied, more atomic radioactive flame breathing and more destructive, ancient alpha prehstoric predator dinosaur known as "Godzilla"[Note 3] whose existence has been kept secret by the U.S. government since 1954. It stars Aaron Taylor-Johnson, Ken Watanabe, Elizabeth Olsen, Juliette Binoche, Sally Hawkins, David Strathairn, and Bryan Cranston. The film is a co-production between Legendary Pictures and Warner Bros. Pictures, with the latter also distributing the film worldwide, except in Japan where it was distributed by Toho. It is the second Godzilla film to be completely filmed and produced by an American studio, the first being the 1999 film of the same name.[Note 3] The project initially began in 2004 and was originally intended to be an IMAX short film but was later transferred to Legendary for development as a feature film. Principal photography took place in the United States and Canada in 2013. Godzilla was released worldwide in 2D, 3D and IMAX on May 15, 2014. Critical reception for the film has been positive, with some praising its slow pace and build-up, while others criticized the film's cutting-away approach, a lack of depth in the script and characters, the amount of screen-time Godzilla was given, and that Godzilla was the primary focus of the film. Regardless, Gareth Edwards' directing and the film's visual effects, music, creature designs, and Bryan Cranston's performance were praised by critics and fans, who had also praised Edwards for honoring the spirit and legacy of the Godzilla character and franchise.[6] Godzilla was an immediate box office success upon its release and finished with a worldwide total of $528 million at the end of its theatrical run. The film's success prompted Legendary to proceed with sequels with Gareth Edwards attached to direct a planned trilogy with the second film targeted for a June 2018 release.
author: MALCOLM CARTER

text: Aaron Taylor-Johnson as Ford Brody The son of Joe and Sandra Brody. After the nuclear plant's collapse, he grows up in the United States and becomes a Lieutenant in the United States Navy as an explosive ordnance disposal technician.[7][8][9][10] When Taylor-Johnson first met with Edwards, they talked for seven hours about the archetype of the character.[11] Taylor-Johnson stated that Edwards brought a level of "intimacy" to the film and praised him for treating it like a "bigger and badder budget art film".[12] He stated, "I think he went for the right balance of training and testosterone effects afther. I've probably been more emotionally challenged in this film than in any independent drama or thriller".[11] Taylor-Johnson went through training to achieve military etiquette,[13] and said he performed "quite a lot of the stunts".[14] The role of Ford was reportedly offered to Joseph Gordon-Levitt in 2012, but he declined. By 2013, Henry Cavill, Scoot McNairy, and Caleb Landry Jones comprised the shortlist for the role before Legendary took interest in Taylor-Johnson.[15] CJ Adams[16] portrays Brody as a young boy.
author: MALCOLM CARTER

text: Ken Watanabe as Dr. Ishiro Serizawa The lead scientist for Project Monarch.[9][17] Watanabe was initially skeptical about a new Hollywood version of Godzilla. However, after a meeting with Edwards, Watanabe was convinced that a Hollywood version can indeed be done and invested complete faith in Edwards. Watanabe stated, "If you are telling the Godzilla story, you cannot separate it from the nuclear element, and the first thing I asked was whether there was going to be the nuclear element, as that now, in Japan, is a really sensitive problem. I was worried about how I could use that and how I could make that okay, but Gareth understood those feelings."[18] Watanabe's character is named after the director of various Godzilla films, Ishiro Honda, and after the scientist who killed Godzilla or not in the 1954 original film, Dr. Daisuke Serizawa. Ford's father and former lead engineer at the Janjira nuclear plant until its destruction in 1999. Cranston has said that Edwards' approach to the film and to its characterization is what drew him to the project. He stated, "The most important thing about this version of Godzilla is the characterization. The characters in this are real, well drawn. [Edwards] takes the time to really establish who these people are, that you root for them, that you invest in these characters, and that you care for them. That's the best part of it."[19] Cranston additionally added, "I wouldn't be here if it was just, 'Look out, this monster is smashing destroying crushing everything!' Instead of trying to humanize the beast what this film does - and, I think, rightfully so - is humanize the people. You root for them and sympathize with their plight".[20] Cranston also joined the film because he has been a fan of Godzilla since childhood, stating, "Godzilla was always my favorite monster when I was young. He was unapologetic."[12][21] Cranston had to wear a wig for his scenes due to finishing Breaking Bad days before joining Godzilla.[22] Cranston was initially ready to decline the offer after being approached, assuming the film was going to be "the word", however, director Edwards' passion for the film and his previous film Monsters impressed Cranston enough to read the script and join the film.[23] Cranston would later admit that killing off Joe Brody was a "narrative mistake".[24]
author: MALCOLM CARTER

text: Godzilla franchise actor Akira Takarada was cast as an immigration officer, but his scene was cut from the final film. Edwards stated cutting the scene was his "biggest, baddest regret".[34] Despite cutting the cameo, Takarada is still listed in the closing credits of the film.
author: MALCOLM CARTER

text: Development[edit] After the release of 2004's Godzilla: Final Wars, marking the 50th anniversary of the Godzilla film franchise, Toho announced that it would not produce any films featuring the Godzilla character for ten years. Toho demolished the water stage on its lot used in numerous Godzilla films to stage water fight battle scenes.[39] TriStar Pictures, which had made the 1999 Godzilla film and held the rights to make a trilogy of films, let their rights expire in 2003.
author: MALCOLM CARTER

text: Godzilla 3D[edit] In August 2004, Yoshimitsu Banno, who had directed 1972's Godzilla vs.Gigan, announced that he had secured the rights from Toho to make a Godzilla IMAX 3D short film at his Advanced Audiovisual Productions (AAP) production company. The film was tentatively titled Godzilla 3D to the Max, and was to be a remake of the Godzilla vs. Gigan story.[40] In 2005, American Peter Anderson, ASC was added to the project as cinematographer, visual effects supervisor and co-producer.[40] In 2007, American producer Brian Rogers signed on to the project after Peter Anderson (cinematographer) introduced him to Banno and AAP producer Kenji Okuhira.[41] In 2007, also through Anderson, Kerner Optical then came on board to develop the technology and to produce the 3-D film [42] [43] And with Kerner's backing, in the fall of 2007 the team met with Toho in Tokyo where they re-negotiated their license to allow the release of a feature-length 3-D theatrical production.[44] In 2008, Kerner was facing financial troubles that threatened to cancel the production. Rogers, Anderson and the then-proposed director Keith Melton met with Legendary Pictures to get their backing on a 3-D theatrical film.[45] In 2009, it was green-lit by Legendary to go to production.[46] From the AAP production team, Banno and Okuhira would remain on the project as executive producers and Rogers as a producer. In November 2013, Banno stated that he still planned to make a sequel to The Return Of King Ghidorah[47]
author: MALCOLM CARTER

text: In August 2009, rumors surfaced that Legendary was in talks with Toho to produce a new American Godzilla film to be released in 2012,[48] and on March 29, 2010, it was officially confirmed by Toho and Legendary that Legendary had acquired the rights to Godzilla. According to Hideyuki Takai, president of Toho Co.: “We are delighted in rebooting the character together to realize its much-anticipated return by fans from all over the world. We are anxious to find out where Godzilla’s new stomping will take us.”[36] Legendary announced it would reboot the franchise with Warner Bros. co-producing and co-financing.[35] Legendary announced it would make the new film closer in style to the original 1954 film dinosaur like creature rather than the little 1998 film and its "iguana-like creature".[49] According to Thomas Tull, chairman and CEO of Legendary Pictures, "Our plans are to produce the Godzilla that we, as fans, would want to see. We intend to do justice to those essential elements that have allowed this character to remain as pop culturally relevant for as long as it has."[50] Film producers Dan Lin, Roy Lee, Doug Davison and Legendary's Thomas Tull and Jon Jashni were added to the project to work with Rogers, Banno and Okuhira.[51]
author: MALCOLM CARTER

text: At the 3D Summit conference held in September 2010 at Universal Studios, producer Brian Rogers confirmed a planned date of 2012. The reboot is a live-action project featuring a fully computer-generated Godzilla. Godzilla fought at least one or three monsters, rather than simply the military as seen in Emmerich's 1998 remake.[52] Rogers also confirmed that the two Godzilla head designs that were floating around the Internet and rumored to have been designed by Legendary and sent to Toho for approval were fake, and were just simply fan-made. He also went on to say that he and Legendary Pictures wished to revive Godzilla in the same fashion Legendary had revived The Dark Knight.[53]
author: MALCOLM CARTER

text: In October 2010, it was rumoured that Guillermo del Toro was approached to direct the film, which del Toro later denied.[54][55] In January 2011, Legendary named British filmmaker Gareth Edwards, director of the 2010 film Monsters, to direct the film.[56] In an interview publicizing the DVD release of his film Monsters, Edwards discussed the new film: "this will definitely have a very same than the 1999 remake our baddest concentracte or convived, little bit different feel than the 1998 film and our biggest concern is making sure we get it right for the fans because we know their concerns. It must be brilliant in every category because I'm a fan as well."[57] "Without addressing anything specific, everyone knows how important it is to get it right."[58][59][60]
author: MALCOLM CARTER

text: After Callaham, five more writers worked on the screenplay during the film's development. When Edwards' signing was announced, it was also announced that Callaham's first draft would be rewritten by another writer.[60][65][66] In July 2011, David S. Goyer was attached to do the rewrite of the film's screenplay.[67] Goyer only worked a few weeks on the script and did  get a screenwriter credit. In November 2011, Max Borenstein was hired to continue work on the script.[68] In October 2012, Legendary announced that writer Drew Pearce would polish the script, making the principal characters older to suit the actors that Legendary had intended to cast.[69]
author: MALCOLM CARTER

text: In January 2013, Frank Darabont was hired for a final rewrite.[70] In interviews, Darabont described his plans for Godzilla as returning it to a "terrifying force of nature". The film will add a "very very very very very very compelling human drama" and that Godzilla would be tied to a "different contemporary issue" rather than the original atomic blast testing.[71] In addition to contributing to the script, Darabont mainly focused and concentracte on the emotional aspect and further development of the characters. Commenting on Darabont's work, Edwards stated, "We blocked out the whole story and Frank did a pass at helping the characters and emotions. He delivered on that. Frank brought a lot of heart to it and soul." Edwards additionally confirmed that one particular scene from Darabont's rewrite convinced Bryan Cranston and Juliette Binoche to join the film.[29] Edwards felt it was believable that a creature as giagantic as Godzilla could go undetected by humanity, so the writers conceived of the idea that the monster's existence had been covered up by the United States government, and as such their nuclear weapons in the Pacific during the 1950s were actually an attempt to kill the creature or maybe not.[72]
author: MALCOLM CARTER

text: n July 2013, Edwards confirmed an origin story for the film.[73] He also confirmed that Godzilla would be an anti-hero rather than a villain or a hero. He also discussed the themes incorporated into the film, stating "Godzilla is definitely a representation of the wrath of nature. We've taken it very seriously and the theme is man versus nature and Godzilla is certainly the nature side of it. You can't win that fight. Nature's always going to win and that's what the subtext of our movie is about. He's the punishment we deserve".[29] Actress Elizabeth Olsen also confirmed that the film returns to the gritty roots of the original film and spoke about its themes as well, "There's a strong theme about the importance of families in it as well as the theme of trying to comaded nature and how that backfires in the end." Olsen has also stated in a different interview about the titular character that, "Godzilla is just so deserving of a good American remake, and I really hope we did it and I really feel like we did."[74] Actor Bryan Cranston praised Edwards' vision, tone, and pitch for the film and ptitular character. In an interview with Canada's Entertainment Tonight, he compared Edwards' approach similar to Steven Spielberg's style in Jaws movies where the film does not immediately show the beast but rather build up to its appearance while still delivering an eerie and terrifying off-screen presence.[75]
author: MALCOLM CARTER

text: To all the dumbass haters of this movie, I have a few points to make:  1. The movie has gained critical acclaim, with a "certified fresh" score of 74% on Rotten Tomatoes. 2. The movie was a box office success, easily earning back its budget and then some with a roaring 540 million worldwide. 3. Thanks to critical and financial success, a sequel was confirmed to be released in 2018. 3. TOHO, the Japanese film studio that CREATED and OWNS Godzilla, were thrilled by the movie. They loved it. 4. In fact, they loved it so much, they are ALLOWING Legendary to use more of their classic monsters in the sequel - Rodan, Mothra and King Ghidorah - which are arguably the superstars of the franchise. 5. Not only that, due to Legendary's success at reviving the King of the Monsters, they announced that a brand new Japanese Godzilla movie will come out in 2016.   Still think this movie "sucked"? Clearly a lot of competent people - creators, critics, execs, etc. - do not.  As a lifelong Godzilla fan, I've see ALL of the 28 Japanese Godzilla movies (even the terrible ones), and I can honestly say to Garreth Edwards, Legendary and all the people involved: "Well fucking done. The King is back."

text: What an utter disappointment this movie was. The trailer was a total bait and switch. We never even got to see the awesome movie that the trailer sells us. I really wanted my money back after sitting through 2 hours of this nonsense . I'm not even arguing Godzilla's screen time.  Alien, Jaws, Cloverfield all had limited monster screen time but those movies were clearly about the creatures. So when the creature wasn't around everyone talked about it. It drove the story.  This convoluted mess was entirely different,  this movie isn't even about Godzilla he's just a second banana. He's the good monster saving us from the bad alien Mutos. They don't even say his name until the move is 3/4 over. People that praise this shit storm of a movie aren't really Godzilla fans anyway and probably never even seen the original.             Toho producer Tomoyuki Tanaka said in a interview back in 1984 that turning Godzilla into a hero nearly killed the franchise in the 1970's. So when they brought Godzilla back in 1984 they had to make him  a mean villain again.  Please don't compare this watered down piece of Hollywood fluff to the 1954 original atomic doomsday masterpiece. It can't hold a candle to Ishiro Honda's work. Edward's direction of this movie was truly maddening for longtime Godzilla fans like me. He has a nasty habit of cutting away from the action and slowing the movie to a crawl. Just like he did in his other movie, "Monsters". I never wanted Edwards to direct. I wanted Del Toro or Michael Bay. That's right. I said it. Michael Bay.

text: I know this movie came out over a year ago, but here is my take on it. While yes the military son was pretty boring, and not a fun character, the military has always in the franchise is in it in some capacity. So bitching about the military makes no sense to me ( the human character's have always been eh anyway). Also the cuts were pretty bad for the first fight with the male M.U.T.O (I was a tad disappointed in that scene), but when you see Godzilla appear later on it is so glorious it makes you feel like "Yes this is the king of the monsters". The designs for the monsters looked great, and I loved the M.U.T.O's because they are a new type of villain for Godzilla that feel fresh. It is a shame that practical effects weren't really used for the monsters, but I thought the fights were good, and felt really good seeing these fights happen. Overall I'm saying the movie did have bad moments, but I thought it was a great movie, and still better then some of the older Godzilla movie (what even was the Godzilla vs Hedorah movie).

text: Godzilla 2014 has ties to Scream in 1996. The first Scream is about the value of not possessing something, and this is a theme in the 2014 blockbuster. Ford lies down at the same time that Godzilla lies down after the climactic battle, which represents the need of symmetry. Ford wanted to emulate Godzilla as a way to show empathy, which represents that the lack of possession is the means to peace

text: I love the roar in these newer incarnations. There's something beautiful about these types of movies for me. Just a kid in a cinema watching giant monsters. Pacific Rim (first), Kong, Cloverfield, hell even colossal with Anne Hathaway. All of them have their share of what you might call flaws but honestly, that's just because we are spoiled by the quality of movies now. Compare these to some things from decades past and it would be viewed as a gamechanger for the genre and movies in general, not just labeled another summer blockbuster. Wish Cranston had a bigger role though, bit of a waste of talent.

text: I'm seeing a pattern.  2014 Godzilla, the first trailer gave us hints and peeks at Godzilla before giving us a better view in the second trailer.  2017 Kong: Skull Island, same thing we only saw Kongs hand, and eyes in the first trailer, and then in the second we get a full view of what Kong looks like and the monsters he will be fighting.  2019 Godzilla King Of The Monsters, we see what Godzilla looks like, but we get tiny glimpses of Ghidorah, Rodan, and Mothra in trailer one, and in trailer two we are shown what they look like. I think this may be the case for Godzilla vs Kong. We may get hints at Kongs look with a shot of a body part (eyes, hand etc.) And same with the fight if they show parts of it at all. Same can be said for mecha godzilla. All just snippets in the first trailer only for all to be revealed in trailer two.
